<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Employment Costs Gain at 4-Year High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Employment costs in the U.S.
increased by 2.9 percent in the second quarter of this year, the
highest gains in more than four years, the U.S. Labor Department
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The gains of American's workers pay in the quarter was higher
than the 2.8 percent increase in the 12 months ended in March and
the highest since a similar 3.2 percent gain in March 1992.
</P>
<P>
The report said that wages and salaries rose 3.2 percent in the
year ended in June, up from 3.1 percent in the 12 months ended in
March.
</P>
<P>
Benefit costs were up 1.8 percent, the same as during the 12
months ended in March.
</P>
<P>
During the second quarter, total compensation rose 0.8 percent,
the same as during the first three months of the year.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Department's Employment Cost Index released today is
one of the two government reports being watched closely this week
for signs of inflation. The employment report with its earnings
component is to be released Friday.
</P>
<P>
As the U.S. economy was expanding rapidly during the April-June
quarter, many analysts expect the U.S. Federal Reserve will raise
short-term interest rates next month to insure slower growth and
keep price increases under control.
</P>
<P>
Consumer prices in the U.S. had been rising at a 3.5 percent
annual rate during the first six months while they rose only 2.5
percent during whole year of 1995.
</P>
<P>
The Employment Cost Index is regarded as the best measure of
labor costs, which represent two-thirds of the price of a product.
The index indicates whether payroll costs are rising so fast as to
force consumer price increases.
</P>
<P>
Although pay represents about three-fourths of total
compensation, many analysts contend the index provides a better
gauge of inflation pressures than the monthly average hourly
earnings report because it also includes benefit changes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
