<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fourth Doping Case Announced in Atlanta </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Russian swimmer Nina Juvaneskaia
failed her doping tests, said Michele Verdier, spokeswoman of the
International Olympic Committee (IOC) here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The 200-meter backstroke swimmer "will be excluded from all the
Olympic-related events till the 2000 Sydney Games", Verdier said.
</P>
<P>
"It's a unanimous decision made by the IOC executive board
under the recommendation of the medical commission," the
spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
Juvaneskaia, who failed to make the final in the Games, was
tested positive to Bromanta, a class A stimulant related with
Mesocarbe.
</P>
<P>
So far, Juvaneskaia became the fourth athlete caught red-handed
of taking drugs at the Games, and also the third from the Russian
Olympic delegation.
</P>
<P>
Early on Saturday, two Russian Olympians and one Lithuanian
cyclist were caught of taking the same banned drugs at the Games.
</P>
<P>
Russian swimmer Andrei Korneyev was stripped of his bronze
medal in the men's 200-meter breaststroke event, compatriot Zafar
Gouleiez was also denied of his bronze medal from the 48-kg Greco
Roman wrestling competition, while Rita Razmaite of Lithuania was
tested positive after her 13th place finish in the women's sprint
cycling competition.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Lithuanian doctor Vitali Slionssarenko, who was in
charge of its cycling squad, and Boris Vasilgev, coach for
Razmaite, were all to be "excluded from all Olympic events till
the year 2000," said the IOC spokeswoman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
