<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Americans Take on Second Job </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Working one job just doesn't seem
to be enough for a growing number of American workers.
</P>
<P>
The Investor's Business Daily reported today that nearly 7.7
million people are holding down two or more jobs. Last year, about
6.2 percent of the U.S. work force was moonlighting, and that
proportion seems to be holding up in 1996.
</P>
<P>
In 1970, by comparison, there were about 4 million Americans
working more than one job -- 5.2 percent of the employed at that
time, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The paper also noted that the Republican Party has seized upon
their growing numbers as a signal that something is amiss under
President Clinton's watch.
</P>
<P>
Since January 1994, a year after Clinton took office, the
number of multiple-job holders has risen by more than 1 million,
the GOP-led Joint Economic Committee said in a recent report
questioning the health of the economy.
</P>
<P>
However, some research shows that more moonlighting does not
necessarily mean that those Americans cannot make their ends meet.
</P>
<P>
Much of the increased moonlighting is among women, and their
motivation does not appear to be completely economic, according to
the paper. Some said they simply enjoyed their second job and
others said they wanted to get extra work experience.
</P>
<P>
But still more than half of multiple-job holders still work for
economic reasons, although the work force has been joined by more
college-educated professionals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
