<HEADLINE> Xinhua International News Summary at 1600 GMT, July 30 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS -- The Group of Seven (G-7) most industrialized states
and Russia today adopted a package of 25 measures to combat
terrorism after a one-day conference on the issue.
</P>
<P>
The practical steps include restriction of terrorists' freedom
of movement, control of fund-raising for terrorist groups and
improvement of exchange of information.
</P>
<P>
The foreign and interior ministers of the eight countries said
in a declaration forerunning the text that they "invite all states
to adopt these measures so as to impart greater efficiency and
coherence to the fight against terrorism."
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Minister Herve De Charette announced at a press
conference today that a team of experts will be formed by the end
of the year to draft a new convention against terrorist bombings
and threats to public transportation.
</P>
<P>
PYONGYANG -- The visit by Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto to Yasukuni Shrine on Monday is an intolerable insult to
the peoples of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK)
and other Asian countries, said the Korea Central News Agency
(KCNA) in an commentary today.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto's claim that he went to the place which enshrines
many World War II criminals in his private capacity cannot
disguise the insidious attempt of the Japanese reactionaries to
revive militarism and to realize the ambition of re-invasion, the
commentary pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto, the first serving prime minister to pay homage to
the controversial shrine since 1985, had paid regular visits to
the Tokyo-based Shinto religious place before, the latest being on
August 15 last year in the capacity of international trade and
industry minister. 
</P>
