<HEADLINE> EC Proposes Retaliatory Measures Against Helms-Burton Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission (EC)
today proposed an EU-wide regulation to retaliate against the
so-called Helms-Burton law of the United States.
</P>
<P>
An EC spokesman said the proposed regulation would prevent
European companies from cooperating with any lawsuits brought
under the Helms-Burton law and other similar laws.
</P>
<P>
He said the regulation must be approved unanimously by European
Union (EU) foreign ministers before becoming law.
</P>
<P>
In a separate decision, the EC -- the executive arm of the EU
-- has begun gathering information required to create a "watch
list" of U.S. citizens and companies that file lawsuits against
European firms.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the EC proposals, EC Vice-President Sir Leon
Brittan said that the Helms-Burtion law "offends and attacks
America's trusted allies, damages business confidence in the
U.S. and beyond and establishes a dangerous precedent that the
United States itself will come to regret if other countries follow
it in the future."
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton signed into law the Helms-Burton
Act in March but decided, under strong pressure worldwide, to
suspend for six months Title III of it, under which lawsuits could
be filed in the United States against foreign companies that
invest in U.S. properties confiscated by the Cuban government
after the 1959 revolution.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Congress last week also passed a so-called D'Amato Bill to
punish foreign companies that do business with Iran and Libya.
</P>
<P>
EU foreign ministers agreed on July 15 to a list of options for
retaliation against the U.S. legislation, including bringing the
dispute to the World Trade Organization, visa requirement for
U.S. businessmen to enter EU countries, a watch list of
U.S. companies filing lawsuits against European firms, and an EU
retaliation legislation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
