<HEADLINE> EC: 14 Countries Have Applied for EU Membership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 30 (Xinhua) -- A total of 14 countries have to
date addressed application for membership to the Council of the
European Union (EU), including all 10 EU associated countries of
central and eastern Europe, according to the European Commission
(EC).
</P>
<P>
The 14 applicant countries are: Turkey, Cyprus, Malta,
Switzerland, Hungary, Poland, Romania, Slovakia, Latvia, Estonia,
Lithuania, Bulgaria, the Czech Republic and Slovenia.
</P>
<P>
The EC said today it was preparing its opinions on the
applications from the countries of central and eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
In the case of Turkey's application, the EC's opinion was given
on 20 December 1989; opinions on Cyprus and Malta were given on 30
June 1993.
</P>
<P>
The Madrid European Council held in Spain last December asked
the EC's opinions to be published "as soon as possible" after the
conclusion of the inter-governmental conference, which is aimed to
update and amend the Maastricht Treaty on political and economic
integration.
</P>
<P>
The opinions will provide both an analysis of the applicant's
current situation and an assessment of the progress they can be
expected to make before accession, taking account of the evolution
of the EU's acquisitions and the changing situation in the
applicant countries.
</P>
<P>
The EC said that the opinions would likely be published in the
second half of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Taking into account the possible duration of negotiations and
time needed for ratification, the earliest realistic possibility
for the next enlargement would be in the years immediately
following 2000, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
