<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Urged to Reduce Budget Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 30 (Xinhua) -- A World Bank official said on
Tuesday the Zimbabwean government should reduce the budget
deficit to five percent of Gross Domestic Product to realise
rapid economic growth, reduce rising unemployment and attract
foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
An ban economic consultant, Tony Addison said Zimbabwe, with a
souring budget deficit of 10.1 percent of GDP, will not be able
to boost both local and foreign investment and achieve
significant economic growth.
</P>
<P>
He said Zimbabwe was in the same situation as was Malaysia 20
years ago.
</P>
<P>
He said political commitment was needed to reduce government
expenditure, which would in turn result in the reduction of
inflation and interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The government has had to borrow from the domestic market to
finance the deficit and this has led to a high inflation rate of
about 24 percent and an interest rate of about 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
Addison said, ''Zimbabwe is at a critical junction. It has to
reduce its budget deficit now. It failed to reduce the budget
deficit to the targeted level of five percent and this is the
reason why the interest rate is still as high as 30 percent.''
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund and World Bank had to withdraw
162.5 million US Dollars in September last year because Zimbabwe
had failed to reduce the deficit to five percent of GDP in the
1994-95 fiscal year.enditem

