<HEADLINE> UK Businessmen Warn Against Gov't EMU Decision Delay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The Confederation of British
Industry (CBI) has warned the government that its determination to
delay a decision on the country's membership of a European
Monetary Union (EMU) may be damaging British interests.
</P>
<P>
In a private evidence to the Treasury select committee, the CBI
said that although it has previously supported the government's
"opt-out" policy on the EMU, it has now believed companies could
benefit from greater certainty.
</P>
<P>
"At Maastricht, the CBI welcomed the UK's opt-out, but now the
value of increased certainty about the scenario may outweigh the
opt-out's benefits in terms of policy flexibility," the Financial
Times newspaper quoted the evidence as saying.
</P>
<P>
The CBI and the British Chambers of Commerce are preparing to
set up the first joint working group to assess the impact on
business of the UK joining or staying outside the EMU.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts say that the move reflects fears that
competitors in France and Germany are stealing a march on Britain
in their preparations for the EMU.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Treasury select committee said in a report that
more MPs were increasingly confident that the "EMU would go ahead
within the next few years at least with an inner core of members."
</P>
<P>
The committee argued that more information should be given
about how the decision on the EMU would actually be taken, saying
"clear guidance on how the decision will be taken would remove one
element of uncertainty for all involved."
</P>
<P>
It also warned the government that without this decision,
British business could be at a disadvantage because the transition
period was likely to pose considerable problems for them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
