<HEADLINE> Protesting African Refugees Hold Demonstrations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 30 (Xinhua) -- About 300 refugees from 12
African countries protesting outside the Pretoria office of the
United Nations High Commission for Refugees (UNHCR) since Monday
marched to the union buildings this afternoon after police
threatened to arrest them.
</P>
<P>
The refugees spent the night on the pavement in front of the
UNHCR offices in central Pretoria, protesting against their
deportation without having found countries in which to resettle.
</P>
<P>
Early in the day, spokesman for the refugee group Denis
Kimwana Nakeya from Zaire told reporters that the demonstration
would continue until the refugees' demands were met.
</P>
<P>
The refugees demanded that the UNHCR and the South African
government delay their deportation while assisting them to resettle
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
Nakeya said the refugees' plight had so far been ignored by
the South African government, the U.N. and other bodies.
</P>
<P>
However, police spokesman Dave Harrington said the protesters
were contravening a law which prohibited a gathering of 12 or
more people without permission from the city council.
</P>
<P>
Police received complaints from the public that the refugees
were blocking the road and pavement outside the UNHCR office and
that they posed a health risk. no ablution facilities exist in
the area.
</P>
<P>
The protesters were given five minutes to disperse or face
arrest. Police told them that being arrested could mean
deportation to their countries of origin.
</P>
<P>
Nakeya said they would present a memorandum listing their
grievances to a government official at the union buildings.
</P>
<P>
The memoranda asking for assistance would also be presented to
nine other countries, including the United States, Canada,
Australia, Switzerland, Belgium and Norway.
</P>
<P>
Among the protesters included refugees from Angola, Ethiopia,
Burundi, Ghana, Senegal, Cote d'Ivoire, Cameroon and Liberia.
</P>
</TEXT>
