<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Seeks Curbs on EU Foreign Policy Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The British government has
reaffirmed its long-standing stance that the European Union's (EU)
common foreign and security policy can be made more efficient
without introducing majority voting.
</P>
<P>
In a six-page submission to the Inter-governmental Conference
on EU reform, the British Foreign Office insisted that the veto
power for each member state should not be abolished in a bid to
enhance the formulation of a common foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
While endorsing the idea of appointing an external
representative of the EU, the Foreign Office also proposed strict
terms of reference for such a representative.
</P>
<P>
The document made it clear that such an official would be kept
on a fairly tight rein by the 15 EU member states and he would
also be answerable to member states through the foreign minister
of the EU presidency state.
</P>
<P>
The official would be responsible for the "external
representation of agreed policies" and "conducting political
dialogue with third countries," the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The representative would have the right to speak for the EU,
but not the right to vote or propose new policies at foreign
ministers meetings, it said.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Office paper also noted that five or six diplomats
should be seconded from the member states to the secretariat of
the European Council to help with planning and analysis.
</P>
<P>
The group would help prepare the agenda for foreign ministers'
meetings, set out policy options and recommendations, and give
early warning of impending crises.
</P>
<P>
However, the Foreign Office said in the document that member
states would have "no formal obligation" to pass on sensitive
information to the council secretariat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
