<HEADLINE> EU Increases Banana Tariff Quota for Non-EU States, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission (EC)
decided today to increase by 353,000 tons the tariff quota for
bananas imported from non-EU countries and non-traditional ACP
(Africa, the Caribbean and the Pacific) suppliers, bringing the
overall quota in 1996 to 2,553,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
The EC said this decision was taken on the basis of the
assessment that for 1996 there will be an increase in European
Union (EU) demand due primarily to its latest enlargement.
</P>
<P>
But the EC added that the increase did not include the
additional 72,440 tons already decided to offset the impact of
tropical storms Iris, Luis and Marilyn earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
According to the EC's forward estimate for bananas in 1996, EU
production will total 750,000 tons, while traditional imports from
ACP countries will reach 680,000 tons. Net consumption in the EU
will be 4,030,440 tons this year.
</P>
<P>
The EU Council Regulation on the common organization of the
market in bananas requires a forward estimate to be drawn up each
year, the main purpose of which is to assess the prospects for EU
production and consumption and provide forecasts of traditional
imports from ACP countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
