<DOCNO> XIE19960731.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Women Workers Suffer Most in Employment in World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Women workers all over the world
suffered more than men in the economic recession of recent years,
the Financial Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
Citing a report published today by the Geneva-based
International Labor Organization, the newspaper said that women
worked longer hours for lower pay, earning between 50 and 80
percent of men's wages worldwide.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that in two-thirds of industrialized countries,
the jobless rate for women has been from 50 to 100 percent higher
than for men.
</P>
<P>
Although women are playing an increasing role in the formal
economy, many jobs for them are part-time or in the unregulated
informal sector where opportunities for discrimination and
exploitation are rife, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It said, "Increasing employment opportunities for women is not
sufficient. There must be action to improve the terms and
conditions of such employment."
</P>
<P>
The report recommended the enforcement of international labor
standards to ensure the principle of "comparable worth by
providing equal pay for work of equal value," greater security for
part-time workers, and "appropriate" labor market regulation to
protect women. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
