<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinians Concern over Settlement Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinians today
expressed their concerns over a possible expansion of the
Jewish settlements in the West Bank, saying such a move
would sabotage the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Meeting in the West Bank town of Bethlehem, members
of the Palestinian Council (PC) discussed the Israeli
government's intention to lift the settlement building freeze
imposed by the previous Israeli government.
</P>
<P>
"The Israeli bulldozers will not only bulldoze the Palestinian
lands in the West Bank, but will also bulldoze the peace process."
PC member Saleh Tamri said.
</P>
<P>
Several PC members urged President of the Palestinian National
Authority Yasser Arafat, who attended the meeting, to break up
peace negotiations with Israel if the settlement activity is
renewed.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian reactions came after a meeting Monday between
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and the settlement
leaders, who emerged optimistic from the meeting.
</P>
<P>
While refusing to make any promises at the meeting, Netanyahu
reportedly gave the settlement leaders one concrete piece of
advice, saying "loud declaration can sometimes sabotage the
actual implementation of plans."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Peace Now, a left-wing organization, today charged
that despite the lack of concrete promises, the government was
already working to increase the settlements.
</P>
<P>
The organization pointed out that the plans of building two
new roads in the West Bank announced by National Infrastructure
Minister Ariel Sharon Monday is the government first move to
expand the settlements.
</P>
<P>
However, Sharon dismissed the sharp criticisms and defended
the plans which call for the beginning of construction of
the trans-Samaria and the Atarot highways in the West Bank
before the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Sharon said that the planned roads were important for the
Israeli security, and would reduce traffic conjunctions for
Israelis and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
He also claimed that both roads were planned by the
previous government led by Labor Party chairman Shimon Peres.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
