<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Defending Champion Defeated in Olympic Badminton Semis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Defending champion Susi Susanti of
Indonesia failed to retain her crown when she was beaten by old
rival Bang Soo Hyun of South Korea in straight sets in the
semifinals of the Olympic badminton tournament here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Bang downed the Indonesian 11-9, 11-8 and gained the final
berths to play against Mia Audina of Indonesia on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"At 7-5 in the second set, my racket string broke and since
then I made some errors," said the 24-year-old Indonesian. "The
draft was no excuse. Bang played better than I did today," added
Susanti, who defeated Bang in the final of the Barcelona Games for
the title four years ago.
</P>
<P>
Susi, is the greatest player in badminton history by taking all
the major competition titles and has been ranked the world number
one for nearly four years.
</P>
<P>
Susanti said possibly she would play badminton for another year
or two, after losing her semifinals today.
</P>
<P>
In the thrilling semifinal match that was keenly contested,
Bang, many times beaten by Susanti in major events, played a
consistent game and finally won the match, taking advantages of
Susanti's unforced mistakes.
</P>
<P>
"I studied all her technics, and I can cope with her play
today," said the joint third seed Bang who won the South Korean
Open and All-England Open this season.
</P>
<P>
Teenager Mia, a talented player for the future, found the going
tougher than she might have expected as she swept aside the
Europe's only women's player Camilla Martin of Denmark 11-6, 9-11,
11-1, winning the berth to meet Bang in the finals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
