<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New ECOWAS Chairman Start Working for Peace in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Barely 72 hours after his election
as chairman of the Economic Community of West African States
(ECOWAS), Nigeria's Head of State Sani Abacha has embarked on
moves to restore peace to the war-torn Liberia, a source told
Xinhua today.
</P>
<P>
The source said, quoting reports from the presidency in Abuja,
capital of Nigeria,General Abacha today summoned leaders of the various
warring factions to a meeting in the city.
</P>
<P>
Although the agenda of the meeting was not immediately known,
it was surely connected with the search for a lasting solution to
the seven-year-old civil war at the next meeting of the ECOWAS
committee of nine on Liberia which will come up before August 18.
</P>
<P>
The source told Xinhua through telehpone that two of the
warlords, Charles Taylor of the National Patriotic Front of
Liberia (NPFL) and Alhaji G.V. Kromah of the United Liberation
Movement (ILIMO-K), were already in Abuja at the time of the
summon, while Roosevelt Johnson and George Boley, the other two
most important figures in the Liberian crisis, are now in exile
and are expected to send representatives.
</P>
<P>
General Abacha's initiative is coming on the heels of the
sharp discussions among heads of state and government at the
ECOWAS summit which just ended in Abuja at the weekend.
</P>
<P>
According to the source, split was caused at the weekend summit
by the suggestion from some member states that the organisation imposes
sanctions against the warlords as a way of enforcing peace and
facilitate the conduct of hitch-free elections in Liberia.
</P>
<P>
Gambian military Head of State yahya Jammed, who moved the
motion,also called for the establishment of an ECOWAS war crime
tribunal to try war mongers and perpetrators of the genocide
which has reduced the country to rubbles.
</P>
<P>
He chided his colleague heads of state who allow their
territories to be used as transit points for shipment of arms and
ammunitions in support of the devastating war in Liberia, the
source said.
</P>
<P>
Jammeh was in Abuja till Monday to put pressure on
General Abacha to do something urgent towards a last resolution
of the crisis, the source said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
