<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Extends Mandate of Observers in Eastern Slavonia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Security
Council decided today to authorize the deployment of 100 military
observers in Eastern Slavonia, Baranja and Western Sirmium in
Croatia for an additional period of six months ending January 15,
1997.
</P>
<P>
In a resolution adopted unanimously today, the Security Council
noted that the military observers were a part of the United
Nations Transitional Administration for Eastern Slavonia, Baranja
and Western Sirmium (UNTAES).
</P>
<P>
The UNTAES was established by the Security Council on January
15, 1995 as a peacekeeping operation for an initial period of 12
months.
</P>
<P>
Following the Basic Agreement signed by the Croatian government
and the local Serb community on November 23 last year, Eastern
Slavonia, Baranja and Western Sirmium would be integrated
peacefully into Croatia.
</P>
<P>
The UNTAES's objectives were to bring the region, demilitarized
and secure, under the sovereign control of the Croatian
government; to retain the multiethnic character of the region; to
promote an atmosphere of confidence among all local residents; to
enable all refugees and displaced persons to enjoy the right to
return freely to their homes; and to promote redevelopment and
reconstruction of the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
