<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dutch Cyclist Captures Gold in Men's Mountain Bike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Bart Jan Brentjens of the
Netherlands averaged a speed of 21.239 kilometers per hour to
capture the gold medal in the first Olympic men's mountain bike
cross country race here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Brentjens, in an orange jersey, cruised through the green
fields and wooded mountainous trails outside Atlanta to cross the
finish line in two hours 17 minutes and 38 seconds, beating Thomas
Frischknecht of Switzerland by two minutes and 36 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Brentjens was the gold medalist at the 1995 Mountain Bike World
Championships, but finished fifth overall in World Cup standings.
Frischknecht won the World Cup in 1995, 1993 and 1992, but
finished second at the World Championships in 1991, 1992 and 1993.
</P>
<P>
Both Brentjens and Frischknecht broke away from a field of more
than 40 riders early in the race.
</P>
<P>
Brentjens paced up in the leading group with Luca Bramati of
Italy and Frischknecht in the chase group with Miguel Martinez of
France before Bramati dropped behind in the second half of the
48.72 kilometer race.
</P>
<P>
Martinez, silver medalist at the 1995 Mountain Bike World
Championships, finished in 2:20:36 to take the bronze medal.
</P>
</TEXT>
