<HEADLINE> South Korea Returns Rescued Soldier to DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 29 (Xinhua) -- South Korea returned a rescued
soldier to the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK)
through the truce village of Panmunjom today.
</P>
<P>
Staff Sergeant Kim Yong-gil of the DPRK People's Army was
rescued by South Korea on July 26 while drifting down the Imjin
River after a heavy rain.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK soldier had been treated at a military hospital before
his return. He was repatriated on humanitarian grounds because he
wanted to return.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the DPRK returned the remains of an American
serviceman killed in the DPRK during the 1950-1953 Korean War to
the U.S. Forces Korea (USFK) through Panmunjom today.
</P>
<P>
Since 1990, the DPRK has returned 209 remains of American
soldiers to the U.S. 
