<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Help Resolve Burundi Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 30 (Xinhua) -- South Africa has been asked
to appoint a representative to work with other leaders in an
attempt to resolve the conflict in strife-torn Burundi, President
Nelson Mandela said today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters at his official Pretoria residence,
Mandela said this request has been made by leaders in the
southern African region.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said a South African envoy will be working with
leaders such as former Tanzanian president Julius Nyerere, who is
attempting to bring about peace in Burundi.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Burundi's Hutu President Sylvestre Ntibantunganya
was ousted and replaced in a coup by military-supported former
head of state Pierre Buyoya, a Tutsi.
</P>
<P>
Civil fightings between Burundi's Hutus and Tutsis have
reportedly claimed the lives of an estimated 150,000 people in
the past three years.
</P>
<P>
South Africa has condemned the military coup, saying it will
not recognize the new government.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Mandela said he has already discussed the situation
in Burundi with Southern African Development Community (SADC)
Chairman, Botswana President Ketumile Masire, and other African
leaders.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that South Africa will not want to act outside
the SADC or the Organization of African Unity.
</P>
<P>
"We will prefer to act through these bodies. It is our firm
policy that we should not act as individuals. We should always
act in a coordinated manner," added the president. 
</P>
</TEXT>
