<HEADLINE> U.S. Leads Synchronized Swimming at Atlanta Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Hosts the U.S. team led the field
of eight with a leading score of 99.200 points after the
synchronized swimming's team technical routine on the sport's
opening day at the 26th Summer Olympic Games here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Americans are now poised for the first ever Olympic gold
medal in the team event which is to be decided after the free
routine is held on the final day Friday.
</P>
<P>
Ranked lower to the Americans after the opening session were
Canadians with 97.933 and Japanese on 97.667.
</P>
<P>
With its unique technical program featuring "The Peacocks"
which drew big applause from the crowds, China, fifth at the World
Cup this time last year here, finished sixth with 94.600 points.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese swimmers complained over sober sound for the music
played for their program today. The official tape was prepared by
the organizers with an original tape brought here by the competing
team.
</P>
<P>
"I almost heard nothing about it at the start," said Guo Cui,
the leading swimmer of China's eight-member squad.
</P>
<P>
"We found this during our pre-competition training and had
talked to the organizers a few times before. But the problem was
still here today. I don't know what had happened," said Chinese
coach Yan Liheng.
</P>
<P>
"But I'm happy with our swimmers' performance today and with
the applause from the crowd. Our swimmers did what they could,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
Though recognized by FINA, the sport's world governing body, in
1952, synchronized swimming became an official Olympics Games
event only 32 years later, at the Los Angeles Games in 1984.
</P>
<P>
Solo and duet competitions were held at the Seoul and Barcelona
Games. But the team event is making its Olympic debut at the 1996
Games here as the only descipline of the sport on the program.
</P>
<P>
So far, only three countries have won Olympic medals in
synchronized swimmig: Canada, Japan and the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
