<HEADLINE> UN Council Extends Peacekeeping Force in Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
today voted unanimously to extend a 4,483-member peacekeeping
force in Lebanon for six months until 31 January 1997.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon was established in 1978 with
the mandate, which expires Wednesday, to confirm the withdrawal of
Israeli forces from southern Lebanon, to restore international
peace and security and to assist the government of Lebanon in
ensuing the return of its effective authority in the area.
</P>
<P>
In adopting the resolution, the council reiterated its strong
support for the territorial integrity, sovereignty and political
independence of Lebanon within its internationally recognized
boundaries.
</P>
<P>
It called upon all parties concerned to fully cooperate with
the U.N. peacekeeping force for the full implementation of its
mandate.
</P>
<P>
In a separate presidential statement read by Ambassador Alain
Dejammet of France, the council expressed concern over the
continuing violence in southern Lebanon and regretted the loss of
civilian life.
</P>
<P>
The council urged all parties to exercise restraint and again
stressed the urgent need for the full implementation of Resolution
425 of 19 March 1978, which, among other things, called on Israel
to immediately cease its military action against the territorial
integrity of Lebanon and withdraw its forces from there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
