<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Reigning world and World Cup table
tennis champion Kong Linghui made up his singles humiliation by
combining with Liu Guoliang to win the Olympic men's doubles title
in an all-Chinese final on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The top-ranked player, who was upset by South Korean Kim
Taek-Soo in a singles match on Sunday, found his flair and form in
the 21-8, 13-21, 21-19, 21-11 victory over Wang Tao and Lu Lin,
reigning world champions and 1992 Olympic gold medalists.
</P>
<P>
Kong and Liu, who have been pairing up for less than one year,
overcame their veteran teammates with angled shots and
counter-attacks to win the first set.
</P>
<P>
Trailing at 5-11, Wang sprained his right ankle and needed five
minutes of outside medical attention.
</P>
<P>
Wang and Lu made it one-all after the younger Chinese duo made
quite a few offensive errors.
</P>
<P>
Kong and Liu, both at age of 20, never gave a chance to their
rivals, who failed to unleash their trademark top spin play and
fast counter-attacks.
</P>
<P>
In the third-place play-off, South Koreans Yoo Nam-Kyu and Lee
Chul-Seung routed Germans Jorg Rosskopf and Steven Fetzner 21-18,
21-13, 22-20. 
