<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- The index of the Kuwait Stock Exchange Market
(KSEM) increased by 16.8 percent from December 1994 to the mid of
this month, a financial expert said today.
</P>
<P>
Board chairman and managing director of the Securities Group
Badr Fahd Al-Humaidhi said that during the period, the KSEM index
was up from 1365.7 points to 1595.8 points, an increase of 230.1
points or 16.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Trading during the first half of this year was also remarkable,
he said. The hike level is higher than the major world stock
exchange markets increase as compared with the Dow Jones
industrial average, which was 10.5 percent, the British Financial
Times index, 0.6 percent, the Japanese Nikkei index, 13.4 percent
and the Hongkong market, 9.41 percent, the board chairman said.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt's Permanent Committee of the Investment
Authority agreed on setting up new projects with total investments
of 163.2 million U.S. dollars and total capital of 63.5 million
dollars. The projects will provide 1925 work opportunities.
</P>
<P>
The committee agreed on setting up a storage project at the
free zone in al-Amriya with a total capital of 250,000 dollars. It
is designed to story medical herbs and read-to-wear clothes and
shoes, according to the latest issue of the Middle East Economic
Weekly, which was published today.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt's Minister of Trade and Supply Ahmed Goweili
said that the ministry will hold intensified meetings within the
upcoming period to develop and promote the Egyptian exports to
other African countries. The Egyptian exports to the African
states stood at 70 million dollars annually, while the Egyptian
imports from them reach 400 million dollars annually.
</P>
<P>
Al-Nasr company, which is responsible for exports to African
countries, has 25 offices across the continent.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt's Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of
Agriculture Youssef Wali said Monday the ministry reduced the use
of pesticides from the annual 32,000 tons to 4,000 tons last year.
</P>
<P>
Wali said that the ministry is turning to the application of
integrated and biological combating methods to maintain the
agricultural environment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
