<DOCNO> XIE19960731.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Homes Sales in US Down Sharply in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Sales of new homes in the U.S.
dropped by 5.3 percent in June as mortgage rates hit a 14-month
high, the U.S. Commerce Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The department said sales of single-family homes totaled
734,000 at a seasonally adjusted annual rate, down from a revised
775,000 a month earlier. It was also the lowest since 713,000 last
March.
</P>
<P>
The revised total sales of new homes in May, which were
initially estimated to be 828,000, were still the highest since a
784,000 rate last February.
</P>
<P>
The new home sales remained strong in the country so far this
year. Sales topped 700,000 for the sixth straight month, the first
time that has occurred since late 1986 and early 1987. And sales
during the first six months were 18.9 percent above those during
the same period in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The department reported earlier that sales of previously owned
homes also fell in June, the first drop since last January
although the sales in the first six months were up 10 percent from
a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Regionally, sales of new homes in June shot up 26.6 percent in
the Northeast and were up 1.4 percent in the West. But the gains
were offset by a 29.3 percent plunge in the Midwest, the steepest
since a 39 percent decline in January 1994, and a 4.8 percent drop
in the South.
</P>
<P>
The decline of sales in both new and existing homes is an
obvious indication that the housing market in the U.S. is cooling
down due to the rising of mortgage rates.
</P>
<P>
According to the Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp., 30-year,
fixed-rate mortgages averaged 8.32 percent in June, compared with
8.09 percent in May and 7.03 percent last January.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the nearly 1.5 percentage point increase since
January would add about 100 dollars to the monthly payment on a
100,000 dollar mortgage.
</P>
<P>
With sales remaining high, a downward trend would ripple
through the overall economy because of fewer purchases of related
goods such as construction materials, appliances and other home
furnishings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960731.0058 </DOCNO>
