<HEADLINE> Chinese Dong Soars in Olympic Badminton Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Joint third seed Dong Jiong of
China stunned the Malaysian veteran Rashid Sidek in straight sets
to enter the men's single finals in the Olympic badminton
tournament here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese, who currently ranked first in the world, will meet
in the final arch-rival Poul-Erik Hoyer-Larsen of Denmark who
overwhelmed reigning world champion Heryanto Arbi of Indonesia
15-11 15-6.
</P>
<P>
"My strategy worked well and I tried to keep attacking and
breaking Rasid's defence," said the Chinese number one who won
last season's China and Thailand Opens and Chinese Taipei Open
this year. He said he was confident to win the title.
</P>
<P>
After leading 4-3, Rashid's high shots to the back of the court
were saved by Dong's accurate playcings and leaping smashes in the
first game. Dong took the set 15-6.
</P>
<P>
The second set went into a see-saw game when the Malaysian
stepped up his pace and played aggressively. But at 9-5 in favour
of Rasid, the Chinese started to go for his powerful smashes and
managed to catch up with his fatigued opponent 10-10 and continue
to a 17-13 lead.
</P>
<P>
After saving one match point and closed the score at 16-17,
28-year-old Rashid gave up the 52-minute match 16-18.
</P>
<P>
Arbi gave the noisy Indonesian supporters a relief after
leading 9-4 in the first with his formidable jump-smash and quick
attack.
</P>
<P>
But two-time All-England champion Larsen, who is in top form at
age of 30, slowly exerted his grip with superb wristy flicked
overhead drops and contrilled slices and sealed the game 15-11.
</P>
<P>
In the second, the Dane continued to put pressure on Arbi and
pulled his opponent around the court before ending the match with
a 15-11 and 15-6 victory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
