<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Welcomes Mexico's Cooperation in Drug Fighting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The United States today
welcomed the Mexican government's cooperation in the fight against
drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
U.S. State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns told a press
briefing here that the Mexican government "has recently extradited
11 individuals to the United States, including four drug
traffickers."
</P>
<P>
"The Mexicans have also deported two other individuals wanted
in the United States, including Juan Garcia Abrego, who was on the
FBI's Ten Most Wanted List," Burns said, adding that these actions
"are unprecedented."
</P>
<P>
"It's a dramatic departure from historic Mexican policy," the
spokesman noted, referring to the fact that the Mexican government
had not been willing until last year or so to extradite their
nationals to stand trial in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Burns stressed that the Clinton administration regarded the
move as "a very good signal of the determination that the
(Mexican) president is bringing to this effort with us."
</P>
<P>
"And we will continue to work with him," he said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also disclosed that senior U.S. and Mexican
officials were meeting at the White House to discuss tougher
measures against drug trafficking. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
