<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Strives for Environmental Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria said today it has made
adequate provisions for the protection of the environment against
pollution.
</P>
<P>
The federal government has enacted anti-pollution decrees and
set up the Federal Environmental Protection Agency (FEPA) to
enforce them, Chief of General Staff Oladipo Diya said.
</P>
<P>
The FEPA's activities have had a great impact on Nigerians,
especially those living in urban areas where industries and
manufacturing firms generated wastes which could pollute the
environment.
</P>
<P>
Diya, the second most powerful man in the country, was in
Lagos, the largest industrialized city in Nigeria, to inaugurate
the country's largest sewage treatment plant, the News Agency of
Nigeria reported.
</P>
<P>
The completion of the plant will help strengthen the efforts
of the federal government to provide an enabling environment for
the establishment, growth and sustenance of industries in the
country, he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the FEPA's Director-General Evans Aina said that
the 5,000 indentified industries in the country generate about
178,000 tons of waste annually.
</P>
<P>
To save cost, the FEPA has advocated that industries with
similar production processes should consider the establishment of
a joint or central waste treatment facility, the official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
