<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Beat Germany to Enter Semis at Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese women's volleyball
team swept Germany 15-12, 15-8 and 15-8 on Tuesday to move up to
the semifinals at the Centennial Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
"We have attained our aim to become the top four squads here
and we are so delighted with the result," said Lang Ping, head
coach of the Chinese that only placed seventh in the Barcelona
Olympics after five world titles in a row from 1981-86.
</P>
<P>
With the win of the quarterfinals, China will play the winner
between Russia and the Netherlands on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese displayed their masterfull ball-handling and
defensive skills to blunder the German attacks before unleasing
scoring counter-punches, paced by hitters Li Yan and Sun Yue.
</P>
<P>
In the first set, Germany enjoyed their early lead of 6-3, 8-5
and 12-11 with steady serves and fierce back-court attacks, but
China rallied back to control the court through solid blocks over
the net since then.
</P>
<P>
"China's defense and attacking downed our team, and we had
trouble in blocking," said German coach Siegfried Kohler.
</P>
<P>
"We have really made a big step in the world arena," Lang said,
"Our goal has been realized through the efforts of my players and
the cooperation of assistant coach apart from my perfonal
contribution."
</P>
<P>
Ace spiker Sun Yue stole the spotlight for China with 18 kills
while Lai Yawang added 14 kills and four blocks.
</P>
<P>
For Germany, Nancy Celis led with 15 kills and Sylvia Roll
pounded 14.
</P>
<P>
However, the Germans have to settle for battles vying for the
5-8 places to be started on Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
