<HEADLINE> Preparations For Summit On Burundi Finalized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Preparations have been
finalized for a one-day emergency Great Lakes summit to discuss
the Burundi crisis in the wake of last Thursday's military coup
in that country.
</P>
<P>
Briefing the press in Arusha, Northern Tanzania, this
afternoon, Information Director of the Tanzanian Foreign Ministry
Cyprian Majengo announced the summit would start at 9:00 am
(local time) tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
He said the ministerial technical committee comprising
ministers for foreign affairs, defence and home affairs was
expected to meet late this evening.
</P>
<P>
According to a report reaching here from Arusha, confirming to
attend the summit are presidents of Kenya, Rwanda, Uganda and
Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Former OAU chairman Ethiopia and the current chairman Cameroon
have also been invited. Zaire will send a representative.
</P>
<P>
OAU Secretary General Salim Ahmed Salim and former Tanzanian
President Juliuus Nyerere who is also the mediator of Burundi
peace process will also attend the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Most of the invited African heads of state are expected to
arrive in the northern town of Tanzania by this evening.
</P>
<P>
Last Saturday, President Benjamin Mkapa and former president
Nyerere were in Uganda for talks with President Yoweri Museveni
for a unified position on the Burundi crisis.
</P>
<P>
OAU has so far refused to recognize Major Pierre Buyoya as the
new leader of Burundi, who took over power last Thursday from the
democratically-elected Hutu President, Sylvestre Ntibatunganya.
</P>
