<HEADLINE> Mandela Bemoans Public Debate on Holomisa's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 30 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela today bemoaned the public debate about the
dismissal of Bantu Holomisa as Deputy Minister of Environmental
Affairs and Tourism, but he again declined to give reasons for
the move.
</P>
<P>
"It is regrettable that a person who holds a responsible
position can go public on a matter of this nature, without having
first finding out why we took this decision," said the president
at his official Pretoria residence.
</P>
<P>
Mandela also told reporters: "We give no reasons for replacing
the deputy minister, and I will give no reasons here."
</P>
<P>
Holomisa was dismissed as a deputy minister by Mandela last
week.
</P>
<P>
His dismissal reportedly came after criticism by the African
National Congress (ANC) of Holomisa's testimony early this year
before the Truth and Reconciliation Commission that Public
Enterprises Minister Stella Sigcau had accepted a bribe from
former Transkei president George Matanzima.
</P>
<P>
Holomisa faces an ANC disciplinary inquiry into his testimony.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Truth and Reconciliation Deputy Chairman Alex
Boraine reportedly demanded that the ANC urgently provide reasons
for Holomisa's dismissal.
</P>
<P>
If the deputy minister has been dismissed because of his
testimony before the commission, this will make the commission's
task difficult. It might discourage others to give evidence
before the commission, said Boraine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
