<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belarus Leader Accepts Two Ministers' Resignation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 30 (Xinhua)--Belarus President Alexander
Lukashenko today accepted the resignation offered by two major
government ministers, Leonid Sinitsyn and Georgy Badei, the
Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The resignations were accepted during a joint meeting of the
government and the Security Council, which was held behind closed
doors was dedicated to the results of the country's economic
performance during the first half of 1996 and the economic
policy's guidelines.
</P>
<P>
Sinitsyn, who was Deputy Prime Minister in charge of foreign
economic relations, led Lukashenko's campaign headquarters in the
presidential elections two years ago.
</P>
<P>
He was named presidential chief of staff immediately after
Lukashenko was elected head of state, but was removed to the post
of Deputy Prime Minister later because of differences with the
president, Interfax said.
</P>
<P>
Badei, who was Economics Minister and who had supra-ministerial
powers under a special presidential decree, was not part of
"Lukashenko's team". He had been Labor Minister in the former
government led by Vyacheslav Kebich until 1995.
</P>
<P>
He told Interfax that he had decided to resign because of the
presidential administration's insufficient attention to the
Economics Ministry's initiatives.
</P>
<P>
"For instance, the program concerning Belarus' economic
development for the period until the year 2000 was submitted for
consideration by the presidential administration as early as in
October 1995," Badei said, adding that the program had so far gone
unnoticed.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the meeting, Lukashenko blamed the current
government for failing to turn the poor economic situation around
in the country.
</P>
<P>
"The economy has been in a free fall for the past six years,"
he said, noting that two years was enough to pass judgement on the
Cabinet's ability to run the economy. The president made it clear
that the Cabinet could no longer refer to the previous
government's economic mismanagement as an excuse for its own
failure.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
