<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Consumer Confidence Reaches Six-Year High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. consumer confidence
advanced to a six-year high in July, a leading research institute
reported here today.
</P>
<P>
The Consumer Confidence Index, issued by the New York based
Conference Board, rose to 107.2, a gain of more than 7 points
over June. Consumer confidence is now at its highest level since
May 1990, it said.
</P>
<P>
Both of the widely-watched components of the Index scored
strong gains in July. Consumers' views of current business
conditions jumped to 124, a gain of more than 9 points over June.
Consumers' expectations for the next six months climbed to 96.1,
up almost 6 points over June.
</P>
<P>
The survey is based on a representative sample of 5,000 U.S.
households, according to the researchers.
</P>
<P>
But the vice-president and Economic Counsellor at the
Conference Board, Edgar R. Fieldler, said, "Whether this latest
surge in confidence is a decisive signal that the economy is
picking up steam remains to be seen."
</P>
<P>
"But the latest survey results confirm that consumers are
clearly confident about current economic conditions and anticipate
further economic growth in the months ahead," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
