<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO to Hold Peacekeeping Exercise in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Three NATO member states and 16
NATO Partnership for Peace nations will send troops to participate
in a peacekeeping exercise in the United States, U.S. General John
Sheehan announced here today.
</P>
<P>
The exercise, coded-named Cooperative Osprey 96, will take
place in Camp Lejeune, North Carolina, from the 12th through the
30th August, Sheehan told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
Some 95O troops from the 16 Partnership for Peace nations
including Albania and Uzbekistan will practice and develop their
combined peacekeeping skills alongside soldiers and Marines from
Canada, the Netherlands and the United States.
</P>
<P>
"This is the second large Partnership for Peace exercise we
have here in the United States," said Sheehan, supreme allied
commander Atlantic and commander-in-chief of the U.S. Atlantic
Command.
</P>
<P>
"It's focused on humanitarian and peacekeeping operations, but
what's different from last year, we've added more of a military
dimension to this," he explained.
</P>
<P>
"We're adding the level of sophistication, we're adding the
level of complexity to what we did last year. And what we're doing
is taking many of the IFOR (International Peace Implementation
Force) lessons in Bosnia," Sheehan added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960731.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua International News Summary at 1530 GMT, July 31 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Saudi Arabia and the U.S. today signed an
agreement on moving U.S. troops stationed in northern Saudi Arabia
to a remote air base as a precaution against further terrorist
attacks.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait News Agency reported from Jiddah, a Red Sea port city in
western Saudi Arabia, that the agreement was signed at the end of
the two-day visit by U.S. Defense Secretary William Perry to Saudi
Arabia.
</P>
<P>
A joint press statement issued by the two countries said that
Perry and his Saudi counterpart Prince Sultan Ibn Abdul Aziz
"agreed that the coalition forces will move to new locations on
Saudi facilities."
</P>
<P>
"This will greatly enhance security while ensuring that
missions will continue to be carried out effectively," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI -- African leaders at a summit in Arusha, Tanzania,
today decided to imposed economic sanctions on Burundi after a
military coup took place there last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
They also demanded immediate talks between all parties in the
tiny central African country, a report reaching here today said.
</P>
<P>
"The summit has decided to impose economic sanctions on Burundi
and appeals to the international community to support these
measures," the report quoted a statement issued after five hours
of talks as saying.
</P>
<P>
Landlocked Burundi relies on coffee and tea which are exported
through roads in neighboring Rwanda and Tanzania. It imports all
its petrol and diesel fuel.
</P>
<P>
The summit also calls on the new Burundi leader to undertake
"immediate and unconditional negotiations with all parties inside
and outside Burundi," the report said.
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- The Japanese government today adopted a package of
measures to combat the spreading of food poisoning caused by the
O-157 strain of E. coli bacteria, Chief Cabinet Secretary Seiroku
Kajiyama said.
</P>
<P>
The package includes working out a manual by the weekend on
medical treatment of the epidemic, studying whether to make it a
legally designated infectious disease and stepping up sanitary and
medical treatment methods, Kajiyama said at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
He said that the cabinet also decided to distribute to every
household with newspapers 40 million flyers containing information
on how to avoid food poisoning.
</P>
<P>
The epidemic has spread throughout Japan this year, causing
seven deaths and sickening some 8,700 people, mostly
schoolchildren in the western city of Sakai. 
</P>
</TEXT>
