<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Arabia, US, Sign Agreement on Moving Troops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia and the
U.S. today signed an agreement on moving U.S. troops stationed in
northern Saudi Arabia to a remote air base as a precaution against
further terrorist attacks.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait News Agency reported from Jiddah, a Red Sea port city in
western Saudi Arabia, that the agreement was signed at the end of
the two-day visit by U.S. Defense Secretary William Perry to Saudi
Arabia.
</P>
<P>
A joint press statement issued by the two countries said that
Perry and his Saudi counterpart Prince Sultan Ibn Abdul Aziz
"agreed that the coalition forces will move to new locations on
Saudi facilities."
</P>
<P>
"This will greatly enhance security while ensuring that
missions will continue to be carried out effectively," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. troops are in the kingdom to keep an eye on Iraq which
invaded Kuwait in August 1990, and was evicted by a U.S.-led
coalition force seven months later.
</P>
<P>
The statement also said both Perry and the Saudi Prince
reaffirmed "the determination of both countries to defeat
terrorism and to work for peace and stability throughout the Gulf
region."
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia hosts 5,000 U.S. troops that shoulder the task of
protecting Gulf security.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has expressed a desire to relocate its troops from
their present locations inside Saudi Arabia towns to other positions
that will ensure their security against possible terrorist
attacks similar to the two recent bombings in Riyadh and Al-Khobar in
Saudi Arabia's Eastern province.
</P>
<P>
A car bomb last December killed five Americans and injured 43
others, while a second truck bomb in less then seven months in
Khobar killed 19 U.S. air force servicemen and wounded about 300
others.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. defense secretary reportedly said that Washington
wants to move between 3,000 and 4,000 troops stationed in northern
Saudi Arabia to the Al Kharj base, 60 miles south of the capital of
Riyadh.
</P>
<P>
Americans in Saudi Arabia are on a very high state of alertness
following the two bomb blasts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
