<HEADLINE> China's Breakthrough in Olympic Badminton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, July 31 (Xinhua) -- China scored a historical victory
in badminton as women players Gu Jun and Ge Fei won its first ever
Olympic gold medal in the women's double title at the Olympic
Games here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese, who qualified for the final by beating Denmark's
Helene Kirkegaard and Rukke Olsen in the semi-finals two days ago,
took two easy, straight games 15-5, 15-5 over Gil Young Ah and
Jang Hye Ock today.
</P>
<P>
In a harmonous coordination, the Chinese, both 21, made a
flying start with fierce attacks to obtain initial leads of 5-0
and 12-3 in the opening game. They went on to take the first game
in just 21 minutes.
</P>
<P>
The pair, long trained with China's former world men's doubles
champions Li Yongbo and Tian Bingyi, put off an aggressive
counter-attacks by the South Korenas. With perfect fitness and
speed, they won an upper hand also in the second game of the
world's strongest confrontation in the event for years.
</P>
<P>
"I'd like to extend my heartfelt thanks to all who have offered
their support to the Chinese badminton team. And today's is a
victory we've being expected for so long," said Chinese head coach
Li Yongbo.
</P>
<P>
"They just did much better than we'd expected," said Qian
Kui, coach of the Chinese winners.
</P>
<P>
Another Chinese pair, Qin Yiyuan and Tang Yongshu, took the
bronze medal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
