<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Crime Rate Fell in 1995 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Canada's crime rate fell one
percent in 1995, its fourth straight annual drop, following 30
years of almost constant increase, according to the latest report
from Statistics Canada.
</P>
<P>
The violent crime rate fell by 4 percent in 1995, the largest
annual decline since the survey began in 1962.
</P>
<P>
However, the 1995 violent crime rate was still 36 percent
higher that it was a decade earlier, the federal fact-gathering
agency noted.
</P>
<P>
The rate of minor assaults, which accounted for 6 in 10 of the
almost 300,000 violent crimes, declined by 3 percent. Over the
last two years, sexual assaults have dropped 21 percent.
</P>
<P>
The homicide rate dropped for the fourth straight year,
reaching its lowest level since 1969, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
There was also a general decline in incidents involving the use
of firearms. The number of homicides committed with a firearm
decreased by 10 percent, it added.
</P>
<P>
Despite all this, there has been a growing public fear of crime
in Canada, especially in its large cities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
