<HEADLINE> African Leaders Impose Sanctions on Burundi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 31 (Xinhua) -- African leaders at a summit in
Arusha, Tanzania, today decided to imposed economic sanctions on
Burundi after a military coup took place there last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
They also demanded immediate talks between all parties in the
tiny central African country, a report reaching here today said.
</P>
<P>
``The summit has decided to impose economic sanctions on
Burundi and appeals to the international community to support
these measures,'' the report quoted a statement issued after five
hours of talks as saying.
</P>
<P>
Landlocked Burundi relies on coffee and tea which are exported
through roads in neighboring Rwanda and Tanzania. It imports all
its petrol and diesel fuel.
</P>
<P>
The summit also calls on the new Burundi leader to undertake
"immediate and unconditional negotiations with all parties inside
and outside Burundi,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
Some 150,000 people have been killed in the last three years
of war and massacres in Burundi between Hutus, who are 85 percent
of the population, and Tutsis, who control the army and the state
apparatus.
</P>
<P>
The summit also calls on the government to immediately restore
the national assembly and un-ban political parties.
</P>
<P>
The summit was attended by the presidents of Kenya, Rwanda,
Tanzania and Uganda, the prime ministers of Ethiopia and Zaire,
and the foreign minister of Cameroon.
</P>
<P>
Organisation of African Unity Secretary-General Salim A. Salim
and the internationally-backed mediator on Burundi Julius Nyerere
also attended the summit.
</P>
<P>
Pierre Buyoya, who took power when Hutu President Sylvestre
Ntinbantunganya was deposed on Thursday, was barred from the
Arusha summit and a delegation sent by him was also not allowed
to attend. enditem

=07311446

=07311442
