<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three People Eaten by Hyenas in Somali Town of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, July 31 (Xinhua) -- A boy and two girls were eaten
recently by hyenas in the outskirts of the southern port town of
Kismayo when they went for elopement.
</P>
<P>
They are two couples of which one would marry secretly each
other while the other couple went with them to witness their
marriage and keep them company. the two couples who had only one
AK-47 with a full magazine were attacked by a large group of
hyenas. They hardly killed 10 of the beasts after they run out of
bullets. The boy who had the gun escaped after climbing a tree
while the other three were eaten.
</P>
<P>
To perform an elopement, the young couples should avoid the
presence and awareness of the father of the lady. They should
travel at least 90 km away and meetl an authorized sheikh who can
read them the marriage performance. Through that simple
procedure, the couple can then claim to be a legalized family
after interoducing their marriage certificate offered by the
sheikh and then the parents of the lady are forced to accept that
procedure according to the tradition.
</P>
<P>
Accordion to Sheikh Idle Abdullahi Farah, a moderate Sheikh,
more than 60 percent of the Somalis are born on the elopement
method since the life standard in the country is very low and the
young couples are often poor. The only reason for the young
couples to choose elopement is their attempt of avoiding to pay
dowry to the parents of the would-be bride. Traditionally, the
parents of the lady would be honored by the parents of the would
be bridegroom with some gifts such as a horse and gun when an
engagement is to be made for their daughter and her loved boy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960731.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao to Impose Anti-Smoking Law in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, July 31 (Xinhua) -- A new anti-smoking law has been
passed by the Macao legislative Assembly and will become effective
on January 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The new law has extended the non-smoking area to all places for
health care, whether public or private, including clinics,
chemist's shops and ambulance, places for people of under 16 years
old, places producing or marketing inflammables, libraries,
musuems, public meeting halls, reading rooms, exhibition halls and
within taxicabs.
</P>
<P>
In addition, it rules that smoking is also banned in all
passenger transportation vehicles, like buses and ships, and places
for public reception.
</P>
<P>
Violators of the rules will be fined between 250 Patacas (about
31.6 US dollars) and 10,000 Patacas (about 1,265.8 US dollars).
Fines will double if the violator is found to have violated the
rules for a second time within three months.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the law also imposes more strict restrictions over
the advertisement of cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
The number of smokers in Macao has been rising over recent
years, and people have called for a more effective restriction on
smoking.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960731.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
