<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albania Tightens Food Import and Marketing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The Albanian government has
launched a crackdown on the import and selling of the foodstuffs
that are of poor quality or have passed their sell-by dates, the
local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Agriculture and Food Ministry has been working with the
police and customs authorities in sending inspection teams to
check the food markets across the country.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of the year, more than 1,500 inspections were
carried out, and private retailers who were found selling fake and
expired foodstuffs were fined a total of 1.5 million leks (about
14,000 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
In addition, substandard foodstuffs worth 45 million leks
(about 4.1 million dollars) were destroyed during this period.
They included chicken, wine, chocolate, drinks and ice cream.
</P>
<P>
Since the early 1990s, Albania has been importing large amounts
of foodstuffs to make up domestic shortages. But a considerable
proportion of imported foodstuffs are either of poor quality or
past their sell-by dates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
