<HEADLINE> 5.2 Million Kenyan Children to Be Immunized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Kenya, in conjunction with the
World Health Organization (WHO), will immunize 5.2 million
children under the age of five years against polio in the two
coming months, the Kenyan Health Minister said today.
</P>
<P>
Launching the national polio eradication campaign here today,
Kenyan Minister for Health Joshua Angatia said 5,000 immunization
centres have been established countrywide, which will be operated
by a combined force of over 15,000 medical workers and
volunteers.
</P>
<P>
The polio eradication campaign will be carried out separately
on August 10-11 and September 14-15.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan Government is undertaking this ambitious project to
eliminate polio from the country by the year of 2,000, the
minister said.
</P>
<P>
The project is in line with the World Health Assembly global
immunization initiative intended to ensure that polio is
eradicated from the face of the earth by the year of 2,000, he
added.
</P>
<P>
WHO's Kenya Representative, Paul Chuke, said effective routine
immunization program with high coverage will create a solid
foundation for bringing polio eradication to fruition among other
strategies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
