<HEADLINE> African Leaders Hold Closed-Door Talks on Burundi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 31 (Xinhua) -- African leaders held closed-door
talks on the Burundi crisis in the northern Tanzanian town of
Arusha before a summit opens later today.
</P>
<P>
According to a report available here, the presidents of Kenya,
Rwanda, Tanzania and Uganda, the prime ministers of Ethiopia and
Zaire, and the foreign minister of Cameroon were set to study an
option for military intervention in Burundi after a military
coup led by Tutsi-dominated army took place in the tiny central
African state last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Organisation of African Unity Secretary-General Salim A. Salim
and U.S. and European Union envoys also attended the talks.
</P>
<P>
Pierre Buyoya, the new Burundi military ruler who overthrew
former Hutu President Sylvestre Ntibantunganya in the coup, was
barred from the talks, the report said. His delegation in Arusha
was regarded as a lobby group.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted an unnamed Kenyan presidential official as
telling reporters that the leaders are expected to agree on
action on Burundi -- either a regional peacekeeping force or
economic sanctions against that tiny mountain state.
</P>
<P>
An official from the Military Technical Committee grouping
Ethiopia, Uganda, Rwanda and Tanzania, set up in June by African
heads of state, said: ``The committee has drawn up a plan
for military intervention if instructed by the heads of state.''
</P>
<P>
``It's up to them to decide what to do. But in case they seek
intervention, then we're ready. We have a plan which can be
applied in the Burundi situation,'' the report quoted another
official as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, Burundi's new president, Buyoya, strongly opposes the
proposed foreign military intervention.
</P>
<P>
The report said the plan called for a force of 25,000 troops
to be deployed in Burundi, where 150,000 people had been killed
in a war between Tutsi-dominated troops and Hutu rebels in the
last three years. enditem

