<HEADLINE> Beijing Hosts Banking Know-How Exposition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 31 (Xinhua) -- A new-generation bank cash machine
that can wipe the smile off the faces of cash-card cheats, made
its Asia debut in Beijing today.
</P>
<P>
The ATM machine is a real eye-catcher at the International
Exhibition on Financial Banking Technology and Equipment opened in
China's capital today.
</P>
<P>
Instead of relying on the usual PIN number, the new cash
machine identifies customers by their faces. It has been developed
by Germany's Siemens Nixdorf. Their advanced automatic teller
machine (ATM) has been developed to use clever technology to check
the physical appearance of customers. It is the first time the
machine has been publicly shown in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Organized by People's Bank of China, the showcase event, from
July 31 to August 4, has attracted more than 200 companies from 13
countries. It is the largest, most advanced event of its kind for
the country's financial circles.
</P>
<P>
US giants, IBM and Hewlett-Packard, Sweden's Ericsson, Japan's
NTT Data Corporation, and Germany's Siemens Nixdorf are among the
86 big-name foreign companies at the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
Other items on display include domestic and overseas up-to-date
financial banking technology and equipment, banking computer
systems, banking card systems and equipment, including ATM and
POS, multi-media technology, banking facilities, banking business
handling systems and financial information service systems.
</P>
<P>
During the exhibition there will be 30 technology-exchange
meetings, providing an opportunity for domestic and overseas
financial organizations to exchange computerized financial
services.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to efforts during the 1981-1995 period, China's
financial industry has made massive progress in electronic
technology applications, especially in state-owned financial
organizations.
</P>
<P>
China's financial institutions now use over 250 mainframes,
more than 240,000 personal computers, and 9,000 ATMs. A total of
110,000 banking outlets in the country are equiped with computers.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
