<HEADLINE> Three Gorges Project Receives Steady and Sufficient Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Almost three billion yuan was
injected into the Three Gorges Project, the world's largest
water-control scheme, in the first half of this year, according to
a Beijing-based newspaper.
</P>
<P>
China Electric Power News reports that the financial input was
nine percent more compared with the same period last year, with
1.57 billion yuan from the Three Gorges Project Foundation, and
1.39 billion yuan in State Development Bank loans.
</P>
<P>
The nation adjusted fund-raising policies early this year,
pledging stronger support from the nation's comparatively
developed provinces and the Three Gorges Project reservoir areas.
</P>
<P>
To expedite the money supply for the project, the State
Development Bank opened its Wuhan Branch in Central China's Hubei
province, the first branch in the country, early this year.
</P>
<P>
The loans from commercial banks guaranteed sufficient flowing
funds for construction companies involved in the giant project.
</P>
<P>
An efficient arrangement and fund transfer system is also
ensured by the Three Gorges Project Development Corporation, the
major undertaker of the scheme.
</P>
<P>
Started in 1995, the Three Gorges Project is expected to take
17 years to complete, involving a total investment of 110 to 180
billion yuan. By the end of last February, the nation had poured
11.5 billion yuan into the water-control scheme.
</P>
<P>
China plans to earmark 8.2 billion yuan for the project this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
