<DOCNO> XIE19960731.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO: Iodized Salt Has More Benefits Than Potential Harms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The benefits of universal salt
iodization by far outstrip potential adverse effects like inducing
hyperthyroidism, the World Health Organization (WHO) confirmed in
a study today.
</P>
<P>
The study was conducted in seven African countries to examine
an increase in hyperthyroidism cases reported in 1995 in Zaire and
Zimbabwe following use of iodized salt.
</P>
<P>
In the seven countries of Cameroon, Kenya, Nigeria, Tanzania,
Zaire, Zambia and Zimbabwe, the recent use of iodized salt has
made iodine deficiency no longer a severe public health problem.
</P>
<P>
In Zimbabwe, for example, goiter prevalence in children was
brought down to 9.1 percent in 1995 from 38.3 percent in 1988,
said WHO in a press release issued Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
No clear evidence of hyperthyroidism was found in the countries
studied except Zaire and Zimbabwe, said WHO, noting that in some
areas of four of them, iodine consumption levels rose sharply from
almost null to up to four times the maximum levels it recommended.
</P>
<P>
The problem in Zaire and Zimbabwe might result from
unnecessarily high iodization level of salt due to lower losses
and higher salt consumption levels than earlier expected and to
some batches containing too much iodine, WHO said.
</P>
<P>
The study concluded that salt iodization levels could be safely
lowered in some countries without harming their effectiveness.
Experts urged better monitoring and quality control procedures
from production to consumption levels.
</P>
<P>
In some of the countries surveyed, salt-iodine content varied
much in production -- a situation needed to improve. The WHO said
that good manufacturing practices, including packaging and
storage, would also help ensure proper salt-iodine content,
especially in tropical areas, where heat and humidity badly affect
the conservation of iodine.
</P>
<P>
Today, the majority of the global population have access to
iodized salt. Universal iodization -- fortification of all salt
for human and animal consumption, has been endorsed as a
cost-effective public health alternative against iodine deficiency
disorders, which is a serious public health problem in 118
countries.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, it was estimated that about 1,500 million people
worldwide were at risk of iodine deficiency disorders.
</P>
<P>
The WHO said that globally, about 655 million people suffered
from goiter as a result of iodine deficiency, and more than 20
million others were believed to be mentally handicapped due to the
lack of iodine in food and water. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
