<HEADLINE> Iran Urges Egypt to Withdraw from Camp David Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Iran today urged Egypt to withdraw
from the Camp David Accord as a pre-condition for the
re-establishment of diplomatic relations between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
The official statement was issued by Iran's Foreign Ministry
spokesman Mohammad Mohammadi and was published by the official
news agency IRNA today.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that Iran's stand towards relations with
Egypt has remained unchanged, stressing that Iran will restore its
relations with Egypt only after Egypt officially withdraws from
the Camp David Accord.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Israel signed in 1978 two Camp David agreements. The
first agreement provided for a five-year transitional period
during which the inhabitants of the Israeli-occupied West Bank of
Jordan and the Gaza Strip would obtain full autonomy and
self-government, and the second agreement provided for the signing
of a peace treaty between Egypt and Israel by September 17, 1978.
The agreement made Egypt the first Arab country to make peace with
Israel in 1979.
</P>
<P>
But Syria, Algeria, Libya, the PLO condemned the Camp David
agreements and then pushed the Arab League Council to expel Egypt
from the league in 1979 for its peace with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Iran also severed its ties with Egypt after it made peace with
the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman noted that Egypt's withdrawal from Camp David
will "free that country from being used by the United Stated as an
instrument for the implementation of anti-Islamic policies."
</P>
<P>
He also accused the United States for triggering insecurity in
the region and motivating open sedition against Iran's sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
He said the United States' intervention in this region is the
main factor contributing to serious clashes between Kurdish
factions in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Iran strongly denounced any and all forms of
terrorism, accusing the United States of supporting Israel's state
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
He called on the G-7 ministers gathered in Paris to
counter the American double-standard policy by paving the way
for effectively countering world terrorism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960731.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Import More </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 31 (Xinhua) -- China has thrown open its doors
to exporters from around the world to help meet its massive
development plans.
</P>
<P>
Figures released today in Beijing show that developing
countries are rapidly cashing on China's domestic growth, too.
</P>
<P>
Imports from India rocketed by over 83 per cent in the first
six months of this year compared to the first half of 1995.
</P>
<P>
Australia and Russia both increased their exports to China by
over 50 percent, while Latin American countries, Kazakstan and
Myanmar, as well as Switzerland shipped more goods to China.
</P>
<P>
Hu Zhaoqing, spokesman of the Ministry of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation outlined the global export winners to
emphasis the way China had multi-dimensional access to its import
markets.
</P>
<P>
He said China plans to expand its import of technology,
equipment and materials needed for domestic construction work, to
meet the needs of its economic development and its increasing
market capacity,.
</P>
<P>
Hu gave details of the measures in Beijing today, adding that
China will welcome more involvement from other countries and
regions around the world in the competition for Chinese markets.
</P>
<P>
Hu noted that China, as a huge market, is open not only to
developed nations, but also to developing nations.
</P>
<P>
He said that China's import volume in the first half of this
year totaled US$ 63.181 billion, rising by 11.6 per cent over the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Hu referred to countries whose exports to China grew by the
biggest margin in the first half of the year.
</P>
<P>
China's imports from India picked up 83.3 per cent more than
the previous figure, and from Oman by 74.2 per cent.
</P>
<P>
The increase rate of China's imports from Australia and Russia
were both above 50 per cent, and imports from Iran and the
Republic of Korea grew by 35 per cent and 30.5 per cent
respectively.
</P>
<P>
According to Hu, the growth of China's imports from Canada,
Latin American nations, Kazakstan, Myanmar and Switzerland in this
period were each around the 20 percent mark.
</P>
<P>
The numbers regarding EU nations and Japan were 9.4 per cent
and 7.6 per cent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Hu said that in the first half of the year, China signed 1,303
contracts for technology imports and exports, with the contractual
value standing at US$ 4.494 billion, including 887 import
contracts with a contractual value amounting to US$ 2.579 billion.
</P>
<P>
The contracts of the introduced high-tech projects accounted
for a quarter of the total contract number. Contracts involving
technology transfer, licensing, consultancy and technology
services represented over half of the total, according to the
spokesman.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
