<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Court Exempts Ex-PM Rao from Testifying </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 31 (Xinhua) -- India's Supreme Court today
exempted former Prime Minister P.V. Narasimha Rao from appearing
before the Chief Metropolitan Magistrate (CMM) on Friday in the L.
Pathak cheating case.
</P>
<P>
Rao moved a petition before the Supreme Court earlier today
challenging the Delhi High Court verdict upholding a CMM order
that summoned him to appear as a co-accused in the cheating case.
</P>
<P>
"The matter has been listed to come up before this court on
August 12. In the meantime, we grant exemption from personal
appearance to the petitioner (Rao) before the learned CMM, till
the disposal of the special leave petition challenging the High
Court verdict upholding the summons issued by the CMM," said a
brief order of the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
Britain-based non-resident Indian businessman L. Pathak earlier
testified before the CMM court that he had given 100,000 U.S.
dollars to controversial godman Chandraswami and his associate to
secure contracts for the supply of newsprint and paper pulp to
India on the assurance of Rao, who was the then external affairs
minister.
</P>
<P>
Rao has denied any involvement in the case.  
</P>
</TEXT>
