<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Artist Carves Microscopic Miniatures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The art of carving miniatures has
a long history in China, and many such works illustrate flowers,
birds, landscapes, crafted into objects the size of small seeds.
</P>
<P>
But Artist Zhang Yuanxing's work is different: he carves
microscopic Chinese characters.
</P>
<P>
Zhang recently completed a 20-character poem in four lines
carved on a tiny slice of ivory, one-tenth the size of a sesame
seed. It is the smallest of its kind in the country.
</P>
<P>
Zhang, a retired primary school teacher in Shenyang, the
capital of northeast China's Liaoning Province, has carved many
remarkable works.
</P>
<P>
Zhang once carved 100 poems on eight pieces of jade, each just
three square cm, and each carved with 500 Chinese characters. He
also carved a book, consisting of more than 6,000 characters, on a
15 sq cm piece of jade.
</P>
<P>
All of these minute carvings only can be seen with the help of
a microscope.
</P>
<P>
The 60-year-old artist said that he became interested in
carving Chinese characters on tiny items more than 40 years ago,
when he was in middle school.
</P>
<P>
Once, during a visit to a local museum, he found a small piece
of ivory -- as big as a grain of rice -- on which 117 Chinese
characters were carved. Zhang then decided to study miniature
carving and become a skilled craftsman.
</P>
<P>
To keep his skills sharp, Zhang has carved 500 characters
daily for more than 40 years. He says he now can carve Chinese
characters on any type of object.
</P>
<P>
He usually does his carving aided by a microscope. Sometimes,
when a piece is too small to be seen with a magnified lens, he
carves by intuition.
</P>
<P>
Zhang uses homemade gravers made from 1,000 different
materials.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960731.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Motel Opens in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai has opened its first
motel to cater for the growing army of car owners.
</P>
<P>
The motel, which cost 4.5 million yuan (about 542,169 US
dollars) boasts car wash and repair services, installing a
gasoline station, offering boarding and accommodation and snacks,
and even managing a Karaoke house.
</P>
<P>
Since trial operations started in January, business at the
motel, located on a key state highway, has been booming. The new
motel meets international standards.
</P>
<P>
Experts believe the emergence of such a standard motel is
likely to lead to the birth of other motels in the city, or even
throughout the country, as private motorists take to China's roads.
</P>
<P>
At present there are many small and privately-owned restaurants
and hotels, which provide similar services, along the country's
main highways. But their functions and services are often
sub-standard and leave much to be desired. 
</P>
</TEXT>
