<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Israel Electric Corporation has completed work
on an experimental wind-energy turbine on the grounds of Kibbutz
Ma'aleh Gilboa, north Israel.
</P>
<P>
The turbine, made in Holland, is to produce 500 kilowatts of
"clean energy," according to today's local newspaper The Jerusalem
Post.
</P>
<P>
The 50-turbine wind-energy farm planned for the site, near
Beit She'an, is expected to have a 25 megawatt capacity. The
energy produced at the site is to be fed into the national
electrical grid.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Tourism Minister Mamdul El Beltagui announced
Tuesday that some 1.7 million tourists had visited Egypt in the
first six months in 1996, which represented a 31.9 percent
increase over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
He said that they spent about 10.3 million tourist nights in
the country, up about 29.5 percent from the figure recorded during
the first six months in 1995.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt will start its summer sales Thursday with price
cuts ranging between 10 percent and 30 percent. The sales season
will last one month.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan and the U.S. have signed an agreement under
which the U.S. will supply Jordan with 12 F-16-A jet fighters and
an F-16-B jet fighter for free in next few years.
</P>
<P>
The fighters have passed 75 percent of their age, Egyptian
newspaper Al-Ahram reported today.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, The U.S. will also lease three F-16-B jet
fighters to Amman for 6.5 million U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
