<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao to Impose Anti-Smoking Law From Early 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MACAO, July 31 (Xinhua) -- A new law on the restriction of
smoking, which extends non-smoking areas and limits advertisement
of cigarettes, has been passed by the Macao legislative Assembly
and will become effective from January 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The new law has extended the non-smoking area to all places
for health care, whether public or private, including clinics,
chemist's shops and ambulance, places for people of under 16 years
old, places producing or marketing inflammables, libraries,
museums, public meeting halls, reading rooms, exhibition halls and
within taxicabs.
</P>
<P>
In addition, it rules that smoking is also banned in all
passenger transportation vehicles, like buses and ships, and
places for public reception.
</P>
<P>
Violators of the rules will be fined between 250 Patacas
(about 31.6 US dollars) and 10,000 Patacas (about 1,265.8 US
dollars). Fines will double if the violator is found to have
violated the rules for a second time within three months.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the law also imposes more strict restrictions over
the advertisement of cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
The number of smokers in Macao has been rising over recent
years, and people have called for a more effective restriction on
smoking.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960731.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Cities to Discuss Cultural Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Representatives from the world's
most famous historical cities will gather in the ancient Chinese
capital of Xi'an in September to discuss protection of cultural
relics.
</P>
<P>
About 100 historical cities in 62 countries will send delegates
to the Fifth World Conference on Historical Cities, which is to be
held in this 2,200-year-old city from September 9-12, announced
Wang Xizhao, a local government official in charge of foreign
affairs.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time Xi'an and China to host such an
event. Other cities that have welcomed global guests for the
conference are Kyoto, Florence and Barcelona, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
Mayors and representatives from these and other cities will
discuss events related to the revival of ancient historical
cities, such as Rome, Athens, Cairo, London, Paris, Moscow,
Vienna, and Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
Topics also will cover the relationship between the protection
of ancient culture and the development of modern civilization.
</P>
<P>
A declaration on protection of cultural relics and
modernization is to be published during the conference. The host
site of the next conference also will be named.
</P>
<P>
The first conference was initiated by Kyoto in 1987, in an aim
to promote exchanges and cooperative relationships among those
cities.
</P>
<P>
Xi'an served as the capital of several ancient Chinese
dynasties since 206 B.C., and is now widely-known for its rich
cultural relics and historical sites.
</P>
<P>
But Xi'an also wants to take advantage of its rich cultural
heritage to develop its tourist sector and build itself into a
modern city.
</P>
<P>
In addition to holding an ancient art festival during the
conference, the city plans to attract foreign funds through
investment and trade talks with its counterparts around the world,
the officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960731.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Up On Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Share prices reversed its
downward trend on the Singapore market today as the benchmark
Straits Times Industrials Index gained 28.61 points to close at
2111.76 points.
</P>
<P>
The total market volume was 90.71 million units, valued at
263.56 million Singapore dollars (about 185.61 million US
dollars). Rises overtook falls by 182 to 104, while 283 other
stocks stayed steady.
</P>
<P>
Kemayan Corporation once again was the most actively traded
stock as it posted a turnover of 5.21 million units. It was
followed by Berger International which had 4.01 million of shares
traded. Ber Group was next, having 3.57 million of its shares
changed hands.
</P>
<P>
The Keppel Corporation topped the gainers' list as it rose by
50 cents to finish at 10.7 Singapore dollars. Cycle &AMP; Carriage,
F&AMP;N, and the Singapore Land each gained 40 cents to close at 12.8,
14.2, and 9.05 Singapore dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Transmarco was the biggest loser, declining by
90 cents to finish at 11.4 Singapore dollars. The Keppel
Corporation c97 was 39 cents lower at 1.71 Singapore dollars,
while Samanda Holdings dropped by 25 cents to 6.5 Singapore
dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
