<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria, Cote d'Ivoire Vie for Regional Shipping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The seaports of Lagos and Abidjan
are under the World Bank's spotlight to determine which will be
chosen as a ship and cargo processing center for the west and
central Africa sub-regions.
</P>
<P>
The two port cities, the former is the largest commercial city
of Nigeria and the latter the economic capital of Cote d'Ivoire,
are vying for designation as a load center, a new concept in ship
and cargo management designed to centralize ship traffic in a
given sub-region.
</P>
<P>
Under the arrangement which is already being operated in
developed regions and the Far East, according to press reports
today, a select city will serve as the primary port of call for
all ships with cargo destined for the relevant sub-region and
from where cargoes will be transhipped to other destinations.
</P>
<P>
A study team commissioned by the World Bank has begun
simultaneous analysis of the maritime environment in Lagos and
Abidjan toward designating either city as the load center for
west and central Africa.
</P>
<P>
The bid is critical to Lagos because if it loses, Nigerian
port may be relegated to an appendage of the port of Abidjan and
will handle only small vessels shuttling between the two cities.
</P>
<P>
The timing to make public the result of the current panel
study is yet to be disclosed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960731.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK To Remain Regional Telecom Center In Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong will maintain its status
as a regional telecommunications and information center after
China regains sovereignty in 1997, according to an official with
the Ministry of Post and Telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
Vice-minister Yang Xianzu told a conference on Hong Kong's
economic prospects, in Guangzhou, recently that Hong Kong will
continue to be an international information hub, and its
co-operation with mainland areas will increase after the handover.
</P>
<P>
Maintaining its telecommunications advantage will guarantee the
area's status as an international financial, communications and
business center, which is what the Chinese government wants to
see, Yang said.
</P>
<P>
The volume of phone calls between Hong Kong and mainland areas
was 300 million last year, totalling more than 700 million
minutes, according to Guangdong Telecom News.
</P>
<P>
Yang said that the mainland and Hong Kong have become each
other's largest trading partners in telecoms, with the number of
telephone lines up to 15,000.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong now also serves as the transfer point for mainland to
Taiwan postal and telecom connections. Direct service is still not
available across the Taiwan Straits.
</P>
<P>
Cooperation between Hong Kong and mainland areas on telecom
projects and technical exchanges is also good, the vice-minister
said.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the telecom business will be independently
managed by the government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region after July 1, 1997, and his ministry will play an important
role in normalizing technical standards of Hong Kong between the
mainland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
