<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Blocks Nigeria Airway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The South African government is
accused of scuttling Nigeria Airways' bid to expand its routes to
Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
The result of an investigation by the Daily Times newspaper
which was made public today revealed that the application filed
by the Nigerian national carrier for two slots four months ago
was being tossed round by the South African authorities.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria Airways has planned to begin flights to Johannesburg
last month and appointed a station manager to oversee the
operations. But the application is yet to see the light of the
day.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian embassy in Pretoria and the consulate in
Johannesburg were said to have put in the necessary diplomatic
touch to secure the approval in the past four months with little
success.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources said the South African embassy in Lagos was
not forthcoming in the visa application filed long ago by Nigeria
Airways for its station manager.
</P>
<P>
The embassy, like its home government, was said to have
continued to give one reason or the other for the delay in
granting the visa to enable the manager to go to South Africa in
preparation for the operation.
</P>
<P>
It is learned that the continued delay in the slot approval
was part of South Africa's diplomatic offensive against Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's relation with South Africa, which was very close
after the collapse of apartheid, became sour following the
execution of nine Ogoni minority activists last November, when
President Nelson Mandela took the lead in calling for sanctions
against the Nigerian military government.
</P>
<P>
Later Nigeria boycotted the African cup soccer championship
held in South Africa. In May Nigeria refused to attend the
African insurance organization annual meeting in South Africa
because of alleged discrimination by South African embassy in
Lagos against the Nigerian members of the organization in
applying for visa.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria and South Africa entered into a bilateral air services
agreement immediately after the abolition of apartheid in 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
