<HEADLINE> Former Prime Minister Rao to Appeal to Supreme Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Former prime minister and
president of the Congress Party P.V. Narasimha Rao will made an
appeal to the supreme court later today challenging the Delhi high
court's rejection of his petition, Congress Party sources said
here today.
</P>
<P>
The Delhi high court rejected Rao's petition and upheld the
order of chief metropolitan magistrate (CMM), Prem Kumar,
summoning Rao as an accused in the cheating case involving
UK-based Indian businessman L. Pathak.
</P>
<P>
Rao's petition was to seek quashing of the July 9 CMM order
summoning him to appear at the court on July 24. The CMM later
fixed August 2 for Rao's personal appearance at the court as the
Delhi high court had directed deferment of Rao's presence in the
lower court on July 24 in view of the pendency of the decision on
the petition moved last week.
</P>
<P>
L. Pathak has testified before the CMM court that he gave
100,000 US dollars to controversial godman Chandraswami and his
associate to secure contracts for the supply of newsprint and
paper pulp to India on the assurance of Rao, who was the then
external affairs minister. Rao said that he had nothing to do with
the case and he is innocent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
