<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Environment Protection Complements Economic Growth in Tibet Reserve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, July 31 (Xinhua) -- China is taking a series of measures
to protect the environment of the Qomolangma Nature Reserve, and
at the same time promote local economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The reserve straddles the border between Tibet in southwest
China and Nepal, and covers more than 33,000 sq km, with five
mountain peaks above 8,000 meters.
</P>
<P>
Qomolangma, the world's highest peak, is famed for its
glaciers, forests, grasslands and lakes.
</P>
<P>
However, due to natural and geographical reasons, nearly 80,000
residents in the area remain poor.
</P>
<P>
To better protect the reserve and improve the local people's
living standard, the Qomolangma Nature Reserve Working Committee
recently divided the reserve into three areas: a core zone, a
buffer zone and a development zone.
</P>
<P>
Environmental protection should be backed up by a strong
economy, and vice versa, said Zholma Yangzon, a committee official.
</P>
<P>
And the appropriate exploitation of natural resources and
improved natural environment will ensure the steady growth of the
local economy, she added.
</P>
<P>
The core zone includes seven areas, with the peak of Qomolangma
at the center, that require the most extensive protection, such as
the mountain eco-system, large primitive forests and several
historical sites, she said. Some endangered wild animals and plant
species also live there.
</P>
<P>
Damage to the ecological environment may cause irretrievable
losses. "A single tree, flower or little bird is not allowed to be
hurt in the area," she said firmly.
</P>
<P>
Just outside the core zone is the buffer zone, which is
designed to lessen the impact of human activities on the core
region.
</P>
<P>
The buffer zone should be used as an experimental area where
methods can be developed to protect the natural environment and
explore natural resources simultaneously, allowing man to work in
harmony with nature, she said.
</P>
<P>
Most scientific work on the nature reserve is carried out in
the buffer zone, and some tourism is permitted there.
</P>
<P>
The outermost layer is the development zone, where most local
residents live. By protecting this zone's environment and
improving its resources, the Committee can improve the local
residents' living standards.
</P>
<P>
Development in this zone will be categorized into agricultural,
pastoral and township growth patterns.
</P>
<P>
The central government, concerned with environmental protection
in the reserve, has set aside funds and arranged for officials
with the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation to
supervise the work.
</P>
<P>
Effective protection work in the reserve has attracted the
attention of the United Nations Development Program, which has
agreed to provide 880,000 US dollars for economic development
there.
</P>
<P>
With financial and technical assistance and the continuing
efforts of local residents, Zholma said she is confident that in a
few years, the Qomolangma region's economic development will be as
attractive as its scenery.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960731.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Miners on Strike Against Pay Delay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The Russian Independent Coal
Employees' Union might call for a general strike next week against
delays in the payment of wages, a high-ranking member of the union
said today.
</P>
<P>
"More bigger strikes in the mining regions are quite possible,"
Ruben Badalov, Vice President of the union told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The situation in Russia's Far East has become serious after a
miner's wife attempted suicide Tuesday by lying on a railway track
because her husband had not been paid for six months and could
hardly afford to support the family, the Interfax News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that the workers at the Partizansk mine in
Primorye of the Far East region got only 15 eggs and some cans of
meat and fish in July to avoid massive starvation.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, some hungry children of miners suffered food poisoning
after eating dog meat, the daily newspaper Moscow Tribune reported.
</P>
<P>
So far, some 13,000 miners have joined the strike since it
began 11 days ago and about 10,000 more were expected to take part
in it although the Russian government has sent 45 billion roubles
(8.7 U.S. dollars) to the region to pay part of their delayed
salaries now totaling 130 billion roubles (25 million U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
In Primorye, which is one of Russia's major coal mining regions
with 27,000 pit workers, more than 300 workers from a
hydroelectric plant at Luchegorsk also went on a hunger strike on
Tuesday, demanding for the payment of five billion roubles
(900,000 dollars) in arrears.
</P>
<P>
Interfax warned that the strikes would paralyze the production
of energy resources in Primorye.
</P>
<P>
However, the Kremlin's senior economic aide Alexander Livshits
was optimistic, saying that the government's money would help ease
the problem and a solution would be found to settle the crisis in
Primorye within several days.
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin on Tuesday urged Prime Minister
Viktor Chernomyrdin to solve the problem by launching a thorough
economic reform in the fuel and energy industry.
</P>
<P>
He also accused local authorities of delaying the payment of
the miners' wages.
</P>
<P>
The Moscow Tribune said a large amount of inter-company debts
instead of a failure in timely budget transfers have led to the
wage delays.
</P>
<P>
The paper added that the coal consumers are currently owing the
suppliers about two trillion roubles (400 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Moreover, many Russian companies deliberately delayed the wage
payments so as to have more floating capital, reports said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960731.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reception Marking 69th PLA Founding Anniversary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Defense Minister Chi Haotian today
called for effectively raising the defensive combat capabilities
of the Chinese People's Liberation Army (PLA) under the conditions
of modern technology, especially the modern high-tech.
</P>
<P>
Chi, also vice-chairman of the Chinese Central Military
Commission (CMC) and a State Councillor, made the remarks at the
reception marking the 69th anniversary of the founding of the PLA.
</P>
<P>
China should steadily build its army into a crack force of
well-trained, well-equipped and disciplined officers and men with
up-to-date military theory, appropriate size, scientific and
effective organizations and footing, and with efficient logistic
support, he said.
</P>
<P>
To this end, he called on the army to adhere to the general
requirements set by CMC Chairman Jiang Zemin, namely "be qualified
politically and competent militarily, have fine style of work,
maintain strict discipline and be assured of adequate logistic
support," so as to enhance the defense and military modernization
and provide a strong security guarantee to the nation in its
reform and opening-up process.
</P>
<P>
Reviewing the army's work over the past year, Chi said, the PLA
has become more revolutionized, modernized and regularized in an
all-round-way and scored great achievements in all fields' work
with defense capabilities further enhanced, thus making new
contributions to maintaining the national security and
safeguarding the unity and social stability of the country.
</P>
<P>
As "an army dedicated to the cause of justice and peace," the
PLA has consistently been implementing the Chinese Government's
independent foreign policy of peace and persistently pursuing a
defensive policy concerning national defense, noted Chi.
</P>
<P>
Chi said that the PLA wishes to conduct still more extensive
exchanges and cooperation with the peoples and armed forces of
other countries and is determined to play an active role in
building a still more splendid world.
</P>
<P>
On the Taiwan issue, Chi reaffirmed that the PLA will
unswervingly implement the basic policies of the "peaceful
reunification" and "one country, two systems," resolutely oppose
any schemes and plots of creating "two Chinas" or "one China, one
Taiwan", firmly oppose interferences by any external forces in
China's internal affairs and resolutely combat the conspiratorial
activities within Taiwan island, which are attempted to split the
motherland.
</P>
<P>
"We shall work hard to promote the peaceful reunification of
our motherland but, on no account shall we commit ourselves to
abandoning the use of force. We have the will, capabilities and
ways and means to defend the state sovereignty and territorial
integrity so as to accomplish the great cause of reunifying the
motherland," Chi said.
</P>
<P>
CMC members Yu Yongbo, director of the PLA General Political
Department, and Wang Ke, director of the PLA General Logistics
Department, and Zhou Ziyu, deputy director of the PLA General
Political Department, Ding Henggao, minister in charge of the
Commission of Science, Technology, and Industry for Defense
Industry, as well as commanders and senior officers of the three
services of the army were among some 600 people present at the
reception.
</P>
<P>
Military attaches and deputy attaches of the embassies of
foreign countries in Beijing were also invited to attend.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
