<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Tourists Visit Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Nearly 3.7 million tourists
visited Australia in the 11 months to May 1996, up 12 percent over
the same period one year ago, the Australian Bureau of Statistics
said today.
</P>
<P>
Japan again provided the largest number of short-term visitors,
numbering 755,500, or 21 percent of the total, followed by New
Zealand, the United Kingdom, Singapore and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
The statistics showed a rise of 220 percent in the number of
South African visitors between 1992 and 1996, increasing from
about 11,000 to almost 34,000.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued today, the Australian Tourist Commission
urged the government not to cut funds for tourist bodies, citing
the figures as an illustration of the effective promotion work by
the country's tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
Australia's tourism market, expected to earn 30.6 billion
Australian dollars (23.8 billion U.S. dollars), will attract 8.8
million visitors a year by 2005, the statement said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
