<DOCNO> XIE19960731.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Precious Stones Exploited in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 31 (Xinhua) -- China's exploitation of precious
stones since the beginning of the 1990s has increased the number
of precious stone deposits to more than 200, and those of gem
varieties to 60.
</P>
<P>
China's progress in precious stone prospecting has eased
bottlenecks in the domestic market's gem supply, which experienced
an overnight boom when the jewelry trend hit the entire country in
late 1980s, and continued to grow, according an official with the
Ministry of Geology and Mineral Resources.
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics from the ministry show that the country has
more than 7,000 precious stone shops, and the annual foreign trade
volume for precious stone and jade stands at 100 million US
dollars, ranking China 11th in the world.
</P>
<P>
But gem exploitation has a long way to go to meet people's
demand: most of the popular precious stones sold in the domestic
markets, such as jadeite, rubies, sapphires, emeralds and
diamonds, are from other countries.
</P>
<P>
China's search for gems has been fruitful in the past few
years, as dozens of new mines and varieties of precious stones
have been detected and exploited.
</P>
<P>
Since the late 1980s, China has discovered more than ten
sapphire deposits along the eastern coast, which is covered by a
basalt belt. The Changle Mine of Shandong Province, the largest of
its kind, has formed a production capacity of one million carats,
and is China's first sapphire exporter.
</P>
<P>
All the stones exploited by the mine have a grain size of more
than one centimeter, and the largest weighs about 1,000 carats.
</P>
<P>
The country's largest diamond mine has gone into operation in
Wafangdian of Liaoning Province, generating an output of more than
100,000 carats every year.
</P>
<P>
Ruby and emerald deposits were found in mountainous Yunnan
Province of southwest China, according to ministry sources.
</P>
<P>
The jade output has grown at a stable rate over the past five
years. The Xiuyan Jade Mine in Liaoning Province, the largest jade
supplier of China, has improved its yearly production capacity to
10 million tons.
</P>
<P>
However, the country's annual output of popular precious gems,
especially diamonds, sapphires and rubies, are still behind the
growth in domestic demand, said industrial analysts in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The prospection of precious stone deposits and exploitation in
scale should be the key tasks for China's geological industry in
the coming years, analysts said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
