<DOCNO> XIE19960731.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Regulations For Foreign Exams in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The State Education Commission
(SEC) has released a set of interim provisions to guide
Sino-foreign cooperation with regard to educational examinations.
</P>
<P>
According to the new provisions, foreign organizations must
work in cooperation with Chinese educational examination bodies
that are at least of the provincial level, and the exams must meet
China's requirements.
</P>
<P>
The foreign organizations should obtain legal authorization
before giving the exams, according to the provisions.
</P>
<P>
The two sides must provide the necessary facilities for the
examination, as well as names of the examinees and of the
organizing bodies, and prove that they are capable of conducting
the exam, the provisions state.
</P>
<P>
The examiners are also asked to provide a list of exam items
and rules.
</P>
<P>
Organizations that jointly give exams can grant non-diploma
certification to qualified examinees. However, the organizations
cannot grant foreign certification to students without SEC's
approval.
</P>
<P>
An SEC official said that foreign organizations began to
cooperate with Chinese educational departments to give exams in
China in the late 1970s, when the country initiated its reform and
opening-up.
</P>
<P>
The examinations have contributed to the improvement of China's
ability to conduct exams, and also to studies of examination
theories.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the new provisions, however, some foreign
organizations failed to follow SEC guidelines in entrusting
Chinese units or individuals to hold entrance examinations or
tests of language proficiency.
</P>
<P>
The official said that such practices, along with improper
publicity of the exams, disrupted the normal educational order.
</P>
<P>
The interim provisions apply with examinees from Hong Kong,
Macao and Taiwan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960731.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flood-hit Hubei Farmers Busy With Farming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Farmers in central China's Hubei
Province are battling against the elements to make up losses
caused by the recent floods.
</P>
<P>
They are fully engaged in farming their fields, trying to make
up for the crop losses.
</P>
<P>
"Farmers are competing with time in taking in early rice, while
planting late rice, straining for a good harvest," said an
agricultural official from the provincial government.
</P>
<P>
The official said that the flood situation is still serious in
the province, through which the mighty Yangtze River runs, adding
that anti-flood measures are still intact along the river and
major lakes.
</P>
<P>
He said that the rainfall which hit the province from July
13-18 was the most severe in its history, causing excessive flood
water to burst river banks and engulf over 2.67 million hectares
of farmland, washing away 360,000 ha of crops.  
</P>
</TEXT>
