<DOCNO> XIE19960731.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq's Return Will Not Disrupt Oil Market: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Iraq's return into the oil
scene in late August will not disrupt supplies if members of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) abide to
their agreed output quota, said former OPEC secretary general
Subroto here today.
</P>
<P>
Iraq is expected to sell about 700,000 barrels per day (bpd)
and if OPEC members adhere by the quota of 25.033 million bpd
agreed in Vienna in June "we would see even stronger prices," he
told reporters after a panel discussion at the Asia Oil and Gas
Conference 1996 here.
</P>
<P>
Subroto, who is now chairman of the Indonesian Institute for
Energy Economics, said current world production of oil stood at 69
million bpd, of which 26 million bpd was supplied by OPEC and the
balance of 43 million bpd by non-OPEC countries.
</P>
<P>
Iraq, a co-founder of the 12-member OPEC, produced more than
3.0 million bpd before a trade sanction was imposed on the country
in 1991 after the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that the over-capacity in most oil producing
nations in Asia, the return of Iraq and the oil development in
Eastern Europe and the former Soviet Union will not paint a rosy
picture for the oil industry beyond 1998.
</P>
<P>
With the oversupply situation, he said "a bearishness in price
is envisaged in the short-term but let us not forget that a
shortage might occur further ahead of the year 2010."
</P>
<P>
The three-day first Asia Oil and Gas Conference, which began
here Tuesday, is aimed at addressing concerns over the limited and
declining supply of oil in the region and at assessing future
trends, strategic issues and challenges facing the petroleum
industry in the Asia-Pacific region as well as exploring new
opportunities in the East Asian market in both upstream and
downstream activities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960731.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
