<HEADLINE> Zambian Hospital Records 874 HIV-Aids Cases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Mansa hospital in Luapula province
of northern Zambia recorded 874 calls of suspected HIV-Aids cases
in the first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed by Noble Chishimba, health director of
Luapula province, in the provincial capital Mansa while
officially opening a week-long psycho-social counsellors'
workshop for health workers drawn from rural health centers in
the province including the Mansa general hospital.
</P>
<P>
The record could be higher should proper recording facilities
have been available, the local daily ''Times of Zambia'' reported
today.
</P>
<P>
''Times of Zambia'' quoted Chishimba as saying that the
workshop and the training for basic psycho-social counsellors
organized by the area health management team aim at imparting
counselling skills to rural staff to decentralize home based care
support systems to the grassroots.
</P>
<P>
The 20 participants at the workshop are to be trained as
HIV-Aids counsellors to be able to give better service to
clients, said Chishimba, ''do not be proud of obtaining a
certificate after the course, but be proud of being more useful
to the community as a result of acquirings new knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
Measures are taken in Zambia to fight the deadly disease of
Aids. There are anti-Aids advertisements seen in streets of
capital Lusaka and other residential centers of the country to
publicize the danger and harm of Aids to the mankind.
</P>
<P>
The advertisements are also seen in TV screens: ''Aids is
incurable but can be avoided.'' People are urged to give up
senselesss sexual habits and drug abuse. 
</P>
</TEXT>
