<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unicom's Business Booming In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 31 (Xinhua) -- United Telecom Ltd. (Unicom), the
Ministry of Post and Telecommunications' only rival in the mobile
telephone business, has reported robust growth since it started
two years ago.
</P>
<P>
According to "China Business Times," Unicom this year launched
its GSM (global service for mobile communication) service in 13
cities. In 1995, the service was available in only four cities.
</P>
<P>
By October, the Unicom mobile telecom network will extend to 28
cities, with a switching capacity of 500,000 channels. Twenty
cities and an additional switching capacity of 500,000 channels
will add to its business by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
By using a special network for the Railway Ministry, the
company is accelerating the laying of a number of long-distance
optical cables that will connect Beijing, Tianjin, Shanghai and
Guangzhou.
</P>
<P>
Unicom's has switching centers for local and long-distance
calls in eight cities and a pilot local call network project that
is well under way in Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
The company will also get involved in the pager business by
establishing paging networks in 10 cities by this August, the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign telecom giants, such as Siemens of Germany, BCI of
Canada, the US's Sprint, and Italy's STET have invested in the
Unicom network, which ranks second in size among China's public
mobile telephone webs.
</P>
<P>
The company expects that the Unicom business will cover all
provinces, municipalities and autonomous regions by the year 2000,
with switching capacity for mobile phones hitting four million
channels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
