<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Business Community Hails New Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Commercial and trade organizations
of Bangladesh hailed the proposed budget for the year 1996-97,
saying that it would help the private sector to flourish and
create a congenial atmosphere for both foreign and local
investment.
</P>
<P>
The Federation of Bangladesh Chambers of Commerce and Industry
(FBCCI) Tuesday welcomed the new budget for its promise to
maintain the process of liberalization of the economy.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Finance Minister Sams Kibria placed in the
parliament the proposed national budget for fiscal 1996-97, the
first budget of the new government formed on June 23.
</P>
<P>
The FBCCI said in a press release that the business community
was happy as there was no new tax, the lock-in for portfolio
investment by foreign investors was withdrawn and there were
proposals to make the subsidies to agriculture explicit, direct
and transparent.
</P>
<P>
The Metropolitan Chamber of Commerce and Industries (MCCI) has
also hailed the proposed budget saying "it will help improve the
investment climate in the country."
</P>
<P>
In a press release Tuesday, the MCCI said the budget has
brought in a long-awaited relief for the tax payers who are
entitled to enjoy the benefits of a simplified assessment.
</P>
<P>
MCCI, however, expressed its concern about the loss-making
state-owned enterprises and suggested early privatization of those
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Imtiaz Hossain, chairman of the Dhaka Stock Exchange (DSE),
Tuesday said that the withdrawal of the lock-in system on foreign
portfolio would help boost the share market, thus accelerating the
industrialization of the country.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, the DSE All Share price index registered a
sharp rise and moved up to 1147.55 from the 1121.09 of the
previous day.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
