<HEADLINE> Xinhua International News Summary at 0830 GMT, July 31 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States on Tuesday welcomed the Mexican
government's cooperation in the fight against drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
U.S. State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns told a press
briefing here that the Mexican government "has recently extradited
11 individuals to the United States, including four drug
traffickers."
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Three NATO member states and 16 NATO Partnership
for Peace nations will send troops to participate in a
peacekeeping exercise in the United States, U.S. General John
Sheehan announced here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The exercise, coded-named Cooperative Osprey 96, will take
place in Camp Lejeune, North Carolina, from the 12th through the
30th August, Sheehan told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Egyptian president stressed on Tuesday that the
"first and foremost" thing to maintain momentum for the Middle
East peace process is to abide by the land-for-peace formula, and
any activities against it should be terminated.
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- A Bosnian Serb delegation on Tuesday met with
Yugoslav war crimes tribunal prosecutors to press for the
indictment of Bosnia's Muslim President Alija Izetbegovic.
</P>
<P>
But neither delegation leader Igor Pantelic nor tribunal deputy
prosecutor Graham Blewitt gave details of the talks this morning,
according to reports reaching here from the Hague.
</P>
<P>
SOFIA -- British Defense Secretary Michael Portillo on Tuesday
expressed the hope that Bulgaria can act as an intermediary
between Russia and NATO.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with Bulgarian President Zheliu Zhelev,
Portillo said NATO has become a bloc ready to cooperate with
rather than confront Russia as it did before.
</P>
<P>
BONN -- Germany paid 1.48 million marks (one million
U.S. dollars) to compensate victims of Nazism last year, or 50
years after the end of the Nazi rule over much of Europe.
</P>
<P>
The payments, by Germany's federal and regional governments,
were slightly less than those in 1994 due to a decrease in the
number of people who were qualified to claim the compensation.
</P>
