<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Commander Foresees Pullout from E. Slavonia by July 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 31 (Xinhua) -- United Nations forces in Eastern
Slavonia could pull out by July 1997 after free elections there, a
top U.N. commander in the region said here today.
</P>
<P>
The withdrawal from the last Serb-held territory in Croatia
would take place after an extension to the peacekeepers' present
mandate, according Belgian General Josef Schoups.
</P>
<P>
Schoups, who is leading the U.N. Transitional Authority in
Eastern Slavonia (UNTAES), told reporters that he foresees a
six-month extension of the 5,000-strong forces' mandate in January.
</P>
<P>
And elections in the currently U.N.-administered region, he
said, could be "organized as soon as possible, maybe by the end of
March," to facilitate the pullout before the end of July.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement signed between Croatia and Serbs, the
one-year U.N. mandate in the region, which comprises 4.4 percent
of Croatian territory, can be extended if either side asks for it.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the Serb assembly in Eastern Slavonia wrote
to the U.N. Security Council, the U.N.'s decision-making body,
asking that the UNTAES mandate be extended for another year.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the request, Schoups said the year-long extension
is "improbable." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
