<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Pays 1.5 Million Marks to Nazi Victims in 1995 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Germany paid 1.48 million marks (one
million U.S. dollars) to compensate victims of Nazism last year,
or 50 years after the end of the Nazi rule over much of Europe.
</P>
<P>
The payments, by Germany's federal and regional governments,
were slightly less than those in 1994 due to a decrease in the
number of people who were qualified to claim the compensation.
</P>
<P>
However, according to figures released today by the federal
government in response to parliamentary questioning, the amount
awarded to individuals saw an actual increase last year.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, 1.13 million marks (750,000 dollars) were for personal
injuries, 102,000 marks (65,000 dollars) were paid to descendants
and 53,000 marks (35,300 dollars) for capital repayment.
</P>
<P>
Government estimations put the total amount needed to pay for
compensations between now and the year 2020 at 25.9 million marks
(17.2 million dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960731.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Austria Wants to Have Presence in Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Austrian Prime Minister Franz
Vranitzky said here today that his country wants to have presence
in Asia by making efforts to enhance diplomatic relations with
Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference here, he said Austria, as a member of the
European Union, does not concentrate only on Europe but also
improves relations with other parts of the world. "We must not be
Eurocentric," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said his visit to Malaysia "clearly set signals" for
developing relations with the countries of the Association of
Southeast Asia Nations (ASEAN).
</P>
<P>
The Austrian leader said that not long ago, he himself visited
China and would visit Singapore soon and his government ministers
have also visited a number of countries in Asia including Vietnam,
India and South Korea, all aiming at boosting relations with Asian
countries.
</P>
<P>
Austria is also expanding relationship with countries in
Africa, Latin America and East Europe, he said.
</P>
<P>
On bilateral relations with Malaysia, Vranitzky said the long-
established Austria-Malaysia relations have been developing "in a
very positive way", but added that the two countries agreed to
make greater efforts to promote cooperation for mutual benefits.
</P>
<P>
The Austrian prime minister arrived here Tuesday for a four-
day official visit.  
</P>
</TEXT>
