<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Biker Wins Gold at Women's Cross Country </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Italian mountain biker Paolo Pezzo
upset world champion Alison Sydor of Canada to seize the gold
medal in the women's mountain bike cross country race here today
at the 26th Oplympics.
</P>
<P>
Pezzo, 27, peddled home in one hour, 50 minutes and 51 seconds
in the 31.8 kilometer race to win the first women's mountain bike
cross country race in Olympic history.
</P>
<P>
Sydor, who won women's cross country race at World
Championships in 1994 and 1995, finished second in 1:51:58 to take
the silver. Susan MeMattei of the United States, silver medalist
at the 1994 World Championships, finished third in 1:52:36 for the
bronze.
</P>
<P>
At the Georgia International Horse Park just outside Atlanta,
Sydor led a group of six bikers to pull away from the field in the
first lap, but DeMattei took over the lead at the beginning of the
second lap in the three lap race.
</P>
<P>
Pezzo, who crashed shortly after the start and walked her bike
on an upward slope, bridged up to the leading group and then broke
away from it half way into the second lap, leaving DeMattei and
Sydor chasing closely behind.
</P>
<P>
"When Paola went by, there was nobody who could really stay
with her," said Sydor. "I thought she was one of the few (who
could win) coming in."
</P>
<P>
With one lap left in the race, Pezzo seemed to have a lock on
the gold medal after building up a 1:31 advantage over Sydor and
DeMattei.
</P>
<P>
"I did't ride as hard at the start as I did at the end," said
Sydor, who shaved seconds off Pezzo's lead when she motored away
from MeMattei.
</P>
<P>
DeMattei, who maintained her pace well into the end, said: "I'm
happy wth the bronze." She said that during the race, she was
"just trying to keep a good pace, and hope that someone would
drop." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
