<HEADLINE> Samper Visits France, Spain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Colombian President
Ernesto Samper was to leave today for France and Spain in a bid
to strengthen Colombia's economic and diplomatic relations with
the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
His first call was to be Paris for a three-day visit to France
at the invitation of his French counterpart, Jacques Chirac,
Colombian Vice Foreign Minister Juan Fernando Cristo said.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, Samper, who is concurrently president of the
Non-Aligned Movement (NAM), was due to attend talks between the
NAM countries with the Group of Seven (G-7) Industrialized
Countries.
</P>
<P>
The tour would also tighten Colombia's bilateral links with
France, Cristo added.
</P>
<P>
Samper's activities in France were to begin with a meeting
with local businessmen, to whom he will explain investment
opportunities in Colombia.
</P>
<P>
A military cooperation agreement will be signed prior to his
talks with Chirac, and Samper is expected to tell Chirac
that Colombia is interested in becoming one of France's main
partners in Latin America. He will present initiatives to attract
French investment in Colombia, especially in the energy sector.
</P>
<P>
The Colombian president will tour Spain starting Friday. He
will discuss with Spanish Foreign Minister Abel Matutes the
installation in Colombia of the United Nations High Commissioner
for Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
Spanish government sources said Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar
would not be meeting Samper.
</P>
<P>
Samper was to be accompanied by Foreign Trade Minister Morris
Harf, Economic Development Minister Rodrigo Marin Bernal and
Hector Moreno, director of the Plan for Alternate Development.
</P>
</TEXT>
