<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deng, Chen to Vie for Women's Table Tennis Gold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- world top women's table tennis
player Deng Yaping downed fellow Chinese Liu Wei, setting up a
final clash with Chinese Taipei's Chen Jing, who routed Chinese
world number two Qiao Hong in the other semi-final on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Deng rallied to beat Liu 21-23, 21-17, 21-19, 21-9, while Chen
beat Qiao 21-9, 23-21, 21-17.
</P>
<P>
Chen, the 1987 world champion, took the advantage of her
rival's complacence to clinch her first victory against Qiao in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
"She had never beaten me in recent several years," Qiao said.
"Therefore I was too relaxed coming onto the court."
</P>
<P>
"I was under-prepared," she added.
</P>
<P>
In the men's singles quarter-finals, two Chinese rallied to
beat their rivals to reach the top four.
</P>
<P>
World number two Wang Tao came back from two sets down to
overcome Vladimir Samsonov of Belarus 16-21, 16-21, 21-10, 21-15,
21-15.
</P>
<P>
Power failure happened twice in the table tennis court and it
might have helped Wang.
</P>
<P>
The first power cut delayed the second set for 25 minutes and
the second postponed the deciding set for 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
"Samsonov's coach asked me whether I would like to play the
rest of the match tomorrow, "Wang said. "I regarded it as sign of
nerves and I said no."
</P>
<P>
China's world number six Liu Guoliang snatched a 9-21, 21-19,
21-16, 21-16 victory over Canadian Johnny Huang, who eliminated
defending Olympic champion Jan-Ove Waldner of Sweden on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"I won the first set because I was faster than Liu," Huang
said. "But Chinese head coach Cai Zhenhua demanded Liu to change
the strategy and it worked."
</P>
<P>
"Liu played rallies with me in the following sets and that got
on my nerves," Huang said. "When I played the ball a bit high or
long, Liu got the kill."
</P>
<P>
In the other men's quarter-finals, 31st-ranked Czech Petr
Korbel upset world number three Jean-Michael Saive of Belgium
21-10, 21-13, 21-19, while German Jorg Rosskopf edged out South
Korean Kim Taek-Soo 12-21, 26-24, 21-12, 16-21, 26-24.
</P>
<P>
Wang takes on Korbel and Liu plays against Rosskopf in the
semi-finals.
</P>
<P>
Early in the day, Kong Linghui and Liu Guoliang beat Wang Tao
and Lu Lin in an all-Chinese men's doubles final. 
</P>
</TEXT>
