<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Lifts Oil Barge from Gulf Bottom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The biggest marine salvage
operation in Canadian history took place today as the Coast Guard
refloated an oil barge that has lain at the bottom of the Gulf of
St. Lawrence for more than 25 years.
</P>
<P>
Powerful cranes on the lift vessels hoisted the barge Irving
Whale off the 67-meter-deep seabed in some 70 minutes, local media
reported today in what's been described as one of the biggest such
operations ever undertaken in the world.
</P>
<P>
The barge, the size of a football pitch, sank in the gulf on
Canada's south east coast in a storm in 1970, with 3,100 tonnes of
oil and seven tonnes of oil containing poisonous PCB chemicals.
</P>
<P>
Now, the Irving Whale is being taken to the port of Halifax in
Nova Scotia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
