<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thousands of Mindanao Residents Protest Peace Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 31 (Xinhua) -- More than 20,000 people staged
rallies and marches in three Mindanao cities on Tuesday in a
protest against the government's peace deal with the MORO National
Liberation Front (MNLF).
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators marched through the city centers of Iligan,
Dipolog and Dapitan to protest the government's plan to set up the
Southern Philippines Council for Peace and Development (SPCPD).
</P>
<P>
Protesters in Dipolog and Dapitan also waved inverted national
flags and burnt effigies of President Ramos to greet the president
who is visiting the region to drum up support for the proposed
council.
</P>
<P>
Ramos ordered the arrest of instigators of such acts, saying
the government would no longer tolerate the "desecration of a
constitutional symbol of the republic."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he sent to the opponents a message, calling them to
"break not the peace," in his speech during the multisectoral
assembly in Dapitan city.
</P>
<P>
The protest occurred as the government reached consensus with
the MNLF to absorb 7,500 MNLF members into law enforcement
agencies, but the issue of integrating 5,000 MNLF fighters into
the armed forces still remained unsolved.
</P>
<P>
In another development the same day, President Ramos announced
that the government and the MNLF have agreed on two revisions in
the interim peace accord to accommodate the concerns of critics of
the proposed SPCPD, but he did not disclose the details.
</P>
<P>
Some senators also said they are willing to meet with MNLF
Chair Nur Misuari in connection with their inquiry on the Mindanao
peace formula.
</P>
<P>
President Ramos tried hard to win the support of 29 Mindanao
officials, the Catholic Bishops Conference of the Philippines and
181 representatives in the congress, but he failed to sway the
senate and the Mindanao residents, especially Christians, who are
the majority of Mindanao society and fear they will be put under
Muslim's control after decades of ethnic conflicts.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
