<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic Briefs (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Mexico expects a 25 percent increase of coffee
production to 5 million bags at the close of the 1996-1997 season,
the Executive Commission of the National Coffee Producers Union
said.
</P>
<P>
During the 1995-1996 season, Mexico's coffee harvest increased
20 percent over the previous period.
</P>
<P>
QUITO -- Ecuadoran banana exports decreased slightly during the
first half of this year, but income for the sales abroad has
increased over the same period of 1995.
</P>
<P>
Banana exports fell 3.2 percent to 1.9 million tons, while
income increased 5.3 percent to 473 million dollars during the
period.
</P>
<P>
Bananas are Ecuador's second major export product after oil.
</P>
<P>
LIMA -- The Peruvian government has started a second round of
reforms to consolidate its market economy, President Alberto
Fujimori said in a message on occasion of the 175th anniversary of
the Peruvian independence on July 28.
</P>
<P>
Fujimori highlighted the level of foreign investment, which
increased from about 1 billion dollars in 1990 to 5.3 billion
dollars at present, and also foresaw more than 10 billion dollars
in investments committed in the next five years.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Japan has replaced the United States to become the
biggest market for Chilean exports at the end of the first half of
the year.
</P>
<P>
Data published by Prochile, a Foreign Ministry organization
aiming to promote exports, showed the Chilean sales abroad reached
about 8.3 billion dollars, in which 1.4 billion dollars were to
Japan, 16.6 percent of the total, and 1.3 billion dollars to the
United States, 16.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
NEW YORK -- U.S. financial analysts forecast that future
contracts and options on Latin American debt bonds will be
negotiated with greater intensity in the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange during the second semester of this year.
</P>
<P>
They said that capitals are going south again. Despite the
rapid and violent price fluctuations, the size of the market will
turn the Latin American Brady bonds into a really important
investment instrument. 
</P>
</TEXT>
