<HEADLINE> Typhoon Kills 7 More Filipinos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Seven more people reportedly died
in floods caused by powerful Typhoon "Huaning," bringing to 62 the
death toll from the typhoon and its predecessor "Gloring,"
according to a report on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A weather forecast said "Huaning," sustaining center winds of
165 kilometers per hour (kph) and gusts of up to 215 kph, had
veered away from the country and was spotted at 5 p.m. over the
Taiwan Straits.
</P>
<P>
Although storm warnings for Luzon island have been lowered, the
typhoon was expected to bring continued rains and isolated
thunderstorms to many areas in the northern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Many areas of Luzon, including Metro Manila, were flooded and
more than 10,000 families have been forced to evacuate from the
areas.
</P>
<P>
The typhoon and floods have seriously damaged the
infrastructure on Luzon island, thus creating one of Metro
Manila's worst traffic jams.  The damage to infrastructure was
estimated at 200 million pesos (7.7 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Since Monday, some vehicles have bumped together while
thousands of commuters were stranded for lack of public
transportation and forced to walk home for up to four hours.
</P>
<P>
The situation in Metro Manila and other areas of Luzon might
become even worse in the near future. According to weather
forecast, at least eight typhoons are expected to visit the
country: three in August, three in September and two in October.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960731.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Hopes Bulgaria Acts as Intermediary Between Russia, NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- British Defense Secretary Michael
Portillo today expressed the hope that Bulgaria can act as an
intermediary between Russia and NATO.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with Bulgarian Prime Minister Zheliu Zhelev,
Portillo said NATO has become a bloc ready to cooperate with
rather than confront Russia as it did before.
</P>
<P>
Portillo said that only those countries which are afraid of
Russia strongly demanded NATO membership. But NATO is prepared to
cooperate with Russia, he added.
</P>
<P>
Portillo and Zhelev agreed that it is impossible to halt the
process of NATO's eastward expansion to include Russia's former
satellite states in eastern and central Europe.
</P>
<P>
Zhelev repeated Bulgaria's determination to join the Western
military alliance.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria should not be isolated by Europe's security body
because its two neighbors -- Greece and Turkey -- have been NATO
members and the other two neighbors -- Romania and Macedonia --
are applying for NATO membership, Zhelev said.
</P>
<P>
Twelve central and eastern European nations stretching from the
Baltic to Mediterranean seas, including Bulgaria, have demanded
NATO membership since 1990.
</P>
<P>
But NATO has kept them waiting because of Russia's strong
opposition. Russia insists that the enlargement process will
threaten its national security. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960731.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
