<HEADLINE> Italian PM Seeks Confidence Vote on Small Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi
today called on the parliament to pass a vote of confidence in his
government in a bid to force through a reduced budget for 1996.
</P>
<P>
Prodi told deputies that he hoped the budget proposal would be
passed without any amendments or additional articles.
</P>
<P>
The draft budget provides for savings of 16,000 billion lire
(about 10 billion U.S. dollars) this year to reduce the public
deficit to around 114,000 billion lire (71 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
A vote of confidence, which the government is likely to win
with ease, will enable Prodi to ignore a series of amendments
proposed by the Northern League which was obstructing the finance
bill. 
</P>
</TEXT>
