<HEADLINE> MPT Set Shanghai-style Service as Example </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Posts and
Telecommunications (MPT) issued a circular urging all departments
to learn from their Shanghai counterparts in providing better
service, "China Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Service quality in the country's monopoly industries has shown
little improvement in recent years, while it has grown at an
annual average rate of more than 45 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to the China Consumers Association, the sector has
been among the top targets of public complaints in most Chinese
cities.
</P>
<P>
Based on a nationwide survey, MPT has found that Shanghai
postal and telecommunications workers, who respond to customer
complaints quickly and setup a public supervision system as well
as a strict staff management pattern, are offering the best
service in China.
</P>
<P>
About 96.9 percent of Shanghai residents surveyed said they
were satisfied with local telecom service, while 94.3 percent were
satisfied with postal service.
</P>
<P>
The paper added that in June, Shanghai Telecommunications
Administration (STA) opened a toll-free telephone hotline to
handle customers' complaints.
</P>
<P>
In addition, more than 2,000 people have been invited by the
STA as public supervisors to help spot bad service in the city.
</P>
<P>
Central Television of China (CCTV), People's Daily and other
national newspapers have reported on the excellent quality of
Shanghai-style Service.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
