<DOCNO> XIE19960731.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic Briefs (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The following are the Latin
American economic briefs.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- The Mexican public foreign debt diminished one
percent during the first half of the year to 99.9 billion
U.S. dollars, the Finance Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Mexico has floated 17 billion dollars in bonds and other
government securities in the international financial markets since
the start of President Ernesto Zedillo's mandate from December 1,
1994. With the revenue generated by these issues and other
incomes, Mexico has been able to pay in advance 7 billion dollars
to the United States Treasury, said the sources.
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- Nicaraguan sales abroad increased 29.5 percent
during the first four months of this year, compared to the same
period of 1995, the Exports Processing Center said.
</P>
<P>
Nicaraguan exports totaled 286.38 million dollars, of which
agricultural goods accounted for 44 percent.
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- Venezuela has become one of the 57 countries with
the highest human development in the world as seen by its
achievements in economic and social sectors, a report
from the United Nations Program for Development noted.
</P>
<P>
Venezuela, ranking 44th among 174 nations, saw its high degree
of human development in the longer life expectancy of its
citizens, which is an average of 71.8 years, and a literacy rate
of 90.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
QUITO -- The meeting of the American-Arab Organizations
Federation (Fearab) started last weekend in Guayaquil, Ecuador's
biggest industrial city.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from Argentina, Paraguay, Chile, Brazil,
Colombia, Uruguay, Venezuela, and Ecuador participated in the
forum.
</P>
<P>
Fearab's Vice President Alejandro Hamed said the national
federation meeting, held once every four months, intends to
promote trade between Latin American and Arab countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
