<DOCNO> XIE19960731.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Continues to Create More Job Opportunities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government is making
fresh efforts to find jobs for surplus urban workers and keep the
unemployment rate in cities at about three percent this year,
"China Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of the year, the country kept urban
unemployment at 2.9 percent, a rise of 0.1 percentage points over
last year, according to the Ministry of Labor.
</P>
<P>
By the end of June, labor departments at all levels helped 1.64
million unemployed people find jobs.
</P>
<P>
This experimental program focuses more on low income and
redundant employees, and has helped alleviate the growing
unemployment pressure.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, local governments adopted preferential
policies to encourage service industries, particularly
labor-intensive firms, to hire more redundant workers.
</P>
<P>
Some service industries were exempt from some taxes and allowed
easy access to bank loans and raw materials.
</P>
<P>
The surplus workers were also encouraged to find new jobs in
private firms and joint ventures after receiving vocational
training.
</P>
<P>
Last year, 1.4 million workers who lost their jobs for more
than six months were re-hired through the help of labor
departments, according to Labor Minister Li Boyong.
</P>
<P>
In the coming five years, China will help eight million jobless
and surplus workers to find jobs, Li said.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, labor departments are phasing in a blanket
social insurance network, which was based on the Labor Law.
</P>
<P>
Of the 30 provinces, municipalities and autonomous regions on
the Chinese inland areas, 29 have formulated programs for old-age
insurance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
