<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Hit By Major Rainstorm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese capital was hit
Tuesday by a heavy rainstorm that deposited over 200 mm of
precipitation.
</P>
<P>
The rain lasted from Tuesday afternoon until early the next
morning, hitting the counties of Shunyi and Pinggu to the
northeast, and soaking downtown areas.
</P>
<P>
There was flooding on some streets, causing traffic jams
Wednesday morning. So far there have been no reports of
casualties.
</P>
<P>
Residents in heavily-hit areas were urged to make an effort to
help deal with the bad weather and in the case of disasters.
</P>
<P>
The local weather forecast said that there will be more showers
over the next two days, and the current hot damp days may last for
about 20 days until the end of the major rainy period.
</P>
<P>
Experts say the storm system is from a subtropical
high-pressure front, an air mass characterized by high
temperatures, high humidity, and high barometric pressure,
conditions that are usually found 30 degrees latitude farther
south. The northward shift has brought it to the edge of the
capital.
</P>
<P>
Although many local people have complained about the oppressive
weather recently, with the humidity hitting a record 98-99
percent, the city is said to be enjoying the pleasantly cool
summer weather of the past five years.
</P>
<P>
So far this summer, the highest temperature here reached only
36 degrees centigrade, two degrees lower than the hottest day in
1992, and six degrees lower than the record hottest day in 1942.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960731.0253 </DOCNO>
