<HEADLINE> Hurricane Kills 50 in Central America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Some 250 people have been
left homeless in western Panama after a river burst its banks in
the heavy rains caused by hurricane Cesar.
</P>
<P>
The Chiriqui Viejo river overflowed and high winds uprooted
trees and knocked out power installations, the National Civil
Protection Agency said.
</P>
<P>
Local residents, including 32 infants and 74 children, took
refuge in Red Cross camps and a gym.
</P>
<P>
But the situation has returned to normal in David, the capital
of the Chiriqui province, the Panamanian authorities said.
</P>
<P>
More than 600,000 people have been affected by hurricane Cesar
which swept through Central America at the weekend. More than 50
people are believed to have died and dozens are missing Panama
national authorities said.  
</P>
