<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Combats Bribery in Medicine Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Chinese pharmaceutical producers
are being called upon by the state to further improve medicine
quality and standardize sales practices to prevent bribery,
reported today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Wenzhou, deputy director of the State Pharmaceutical
Administration, made the call yesterday in Beijing at the launch
of a nationwide quality inspection of new Shanghai-made medicines.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said the drive would help promote the central
government's attempt to regulate sales practices in the medicine
field and to create well-known Chinese-made medical products.
</P>
<P>
Bribery has boomed in the pharmaceutical business in recent
years. Hospital drug purchasers can receive kickbacks of up to 25
percent, which leads to the inflow of substandard or even fake
medicine to some hospitals.
</P>
<P>
The State Council issued a circular in April calling for a
crackdown on sales commissions and illegal sale promotion
activities.
</P>
<P>
The nationwide inspection of Shanghai's new medicines is one of
the responses to the state request and is expected to result in a
new and healthy medicine promotion process, said Chen Tonghui,
deputy director of the Shanghai Pharmaceutical Administration.
</P>
<P>
About 26 pharmaceutical enterprises from Shanghai will
participate in the action that is initiated by the Shanghai
Pharmaceutical Industry Sale Co and supported by the State
Pharmaceutical Administration.
</P>
<P>
Aside from quality inspection, activities will also be carried
out to collect suggestions from patients for improvement in 36
major Chinese cities, recommend some new medicines for medical
institutes and exchange service experiences.
</P>
<P>
An important research, production and exportation base,
Shanghai currently has more than 1,500 varieties of medical
products marketed to foreign countries and regions. More than 200
million US dollars-worth of medicines and medical products were
exported.
</P>
<P>
According to Chen, the municipal government and enterprises
invested 3.4 billion yuan (409 million US dollars) in the past
five years to renovate facilities and techniques and about
one-third of the 28 pharmaceutical enterprises have moved to the
Pudong new industrial development area in Shanghai. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
