<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kazakhstan Wins Modern Pentathlon Olympic Gold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, July 30 (Xinhua) - Aleksandr Parygin of Kazakhstan
took the gold medal of the Olympic modern pentathlon on his debut
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Parygin totalled 5,551 points, ahead of Russia's Eduard Zenovka
who scored 5,530, and Janos Martinek of Hungary with 5,501 points.
</P>
<P>
Favorite Dmitri Svatkovski from Russia, world champion for the
last two years, came up from ninth after four events but was just
edged out of the bronze medal and collapsed on the finish line of
the cross country run with dehydration.
</P>
<P>
Parygin, a 23-year-old sports coach from Almaty, won the
decisive 4,000m cross country at the end of 13 hours of
competition in a photo finish from Zenovka.
</P>
<P>
Zenovka led into the final straight but in a breathtaking
climax tripped just inches from the finish line when running
shoulder to shoulder with Parygin.
</P>
<P>
For the first time at the Olympics, the five disciplines in
modern pentathlon, normally spread over five days, were held on
one day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
