<HEADLINE> Anti-Drug System on Amazon and Orinoco </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Venezuela, Colombia, and Brazil
are setting up a telecommunications system on the Amazon and
Orinoco rivers to control drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
Guillermo Romero Lizarraga, the president of Venezuela's
National Commission Against the Illicit Use of Drugs, said a
modern computerized system had already been installed in several
strategic places on the Amazon and Orinoco. They would begin
operating in the first week of September.
</P>
<P>
The project aims at providing equipment, programs and
computarized training to make possible the use of safe
telecommunications in the triangle border shared by Brazil,
Colombia and Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
The project is sponsored by the National Commission Against the
Illicit Use of Drugs of Venezuela and the Interamerican Commission
for the Control and Abuse of Drugs.  
</P>
