<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hurricane Kills 50 in Central America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Fifty people died and dozens
were missing when hurricane Cesar swept Central America on Sunday
and Monday, Panama national authorities said.
</P>
<P>
Cesar, which became tropical storm Douglas on Monday, left nine
dead in El Salvador and four in Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
In Panama, 246 people lost their homes when heavy rains caused
the overflowing of the Chiriqui Viejo River and the winds uprooted
big trees and affected power installations in the Chiriqui
province, northeast of Panama City, the National Civil Protection
System said.
</P>
<P>
The local residents, including 32 infants and 74 children, have
to live in Red Cross installations and a gym. But the situation
has returned to normal in David, the capital of the Chiriqui
province, the Panamanian authorities said.
</P>
<P>
More than 600,000 people were affected in the disaster in
Central America. 
</P>
</TEXT>
