<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   World Champion Lifts Olympic Title wiith World Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- World champion Andrey Chemerkin of
Russia, who jerked a world record weight of 260 kilograms in his
last lift, became the strongest man in the world, winning the over
108-kg category at the Centennial Olympic Games here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Russian, gold medal winner at the world championships in
Guangzhou, China, last November, snatched 197.5 kilograms and
jerked the world mark weight for a total of 457.5 kilograms, which
equals the world record weight set by Aleksandr Kurlovich of
Belarus in Istanbul two years ago.
</P>
<P>
Germany's Ronny Weller, runner-up to Chemerkin at the Worlds in
China, won the silver medal at 455 kilograms, with 200 from the
snatch and 255 from the jerk.
</P>
<P>
Australia's Stefan Botev, who snatched 200 and jerked 250 for a
combined total of 450, finished third on the closing day of the
weightlifting tournament.
</P>
<P>
After the snatch, it seemed that Botev, who enjoyed lighter
bodyweight against other medal contenders, would win an Olympic
weightlifting gold for his new country. The lifter, who moved
from Bulgaria to Australia, beat Weller and Chemerkin to the
second and third in the snatch.
</P>
<P>
In the clean and jerk, both Weller and Chemerkin hoisted the
world record to a new high in their third attempts.
</P>
<P>
After Weller jerked 255 kilograms to beat the previous world
mark by 1.5 kilograms, Chemerkin went ahead to hoist 260
kilograms, five kilograms more than Weller's lift.
</P>
<P>
Two-times Olympic champion Kurlovich, who had 195 in the snatch
and 230 in the jerk, only finished fifth. The Belarussian, who
was tested positive during a German competition, missed the last
world championships in China.
</P>
<P>
When Chemerkin noticed in the backstage that Weller jerked
255kg, he just added five kilograms. "I know I have to lift that
weight," he said. "But if there is somebody who can lift 260, I
might try more."
</P>
<P>
"The only thing for me here is to win," he added. "And I will
continue my training in weightlifting, for another gold in
Sydney."
</P>
<P>
After ten days of competition, China, Turkey, Greece and Russia
each took two gold medals in the final team standings. Cuba and
Ukraine each had one.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960731.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Earth Quake Hits Island of Luzon, Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 31 (Xinhua) -- An earth quake rocked the main
island of Luzon, northern Philippines, early Wednesday morning,
and slight damages are expected in areas around its epicenter, the
Philippine Institute of Volcanology and Seismology said.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the institute told Xinhua that the epicenter of
the quake measuring 5.8 on Richter scale is Floida Blanca near the
provinces of Pampanga, Bataan and Zambales, about 60 km north of
Manila.
</P>
<P>
Fifteen aftershocks have been registered since the major one,
which hit at 01:38 a.m. the cities of Olongapo, Angeles, Baguio,
Tagaytay and Manila, he said.
</P>
<P>
Emergency monitoring teams were sent to the affected areas to
check reports of quake-induced cracks in buildings and other
structures, he said.
</P>
<P>
Leonardo Roman, governor of Bataan province, said that the
earth quake caused a 150-meter crack in a dike in the village of
Tukop in the town of Dinalupihan.
</P>
<P>
He said that he already ordered evacuation of people who will
be immediately affected by the expected collapse of the Tukop
dike.
</P>
<P>
Roman said that the inevitable collapse of the Tukop dike would
induce main rivers to overflow and cause major floods in
Dinalupihan and nearby areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
