<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Slovenian Medved Qualified for Men's Individual Top Eight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Slovenia's Samo Medved scored one
of his career's most impressive victory as he beat world number
two Jari Lipponen of Finland in an unbelievable way at the Olympic
men's individual archery event here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Medved won the extraordinary second round shoot-out over the
Finnish with his fourth extra arrow. The two earlier tied on 161
points.
</P>
<P>
They each twice scored a nine with their initial shots from 70
metres, which brought the contest into a third extra arrow decided on
a closest-to-the bull basis.
</P>
<P>
And both Medved and Lipponen scored perfect 10s which measured
an identical three centimeters from the centre of the bullseye.
</P>
<P>
And the issue was decided only when the archers reached into
their quivers a fourth time and Medved scored a nine to his
opponent's eight.
</P>
<P>
The 36-year-old from Ljubljana was ranked joint 99th in the
world.
</P>
<P>
His opponent was left to reflect on the fickle nature of
Olympic sport, having registed the highest score of the opening
round with 168 from his allotted 18 arrows.
</P>
<P>
There was no repeat Games joy for 1992 champion Sebastien Flute
of France, who was beaten 161-158 by world number one Martinus
Grov of Norway in the first round.
</P>
<P>
The pair were level halfway through the match, but Grov pulled
away and later beat China's Tang Hua to advance to the last 16 on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Among other qualifiers were Jose Anchondo of Mexico, who beat
Raul Kivilo of Estonia 158-157. He went on to win over then beat
18-arrow world record holder Vadim Chikarev of Kazakhstan by two
points in the second round. 
</P>
</TEXT>
