<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weightlifters Steal Show at Atlanta Olympics Tuesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Russian and German weightlifters
Andrey Chemerkin and Ronny Weller came to the limelight when they
put up record-breaking performances in the over-180kg
weightlifting competition of the 26th Olympic Games here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The German strongman jerked 255kg to smash the old world mark
of 235.5kg set by Chemerkin in May 1995.
</P>
<P>
A few minutes later, the Russian came forward and lifted 260kg
to rewrite the record and make it his own again.
</P>
<P>
The gold medal in this event was won by the Russian on a
two-lift total of 457.5 kilograms, which equalled the existing
world mark held by Aleksandr Kurlovich.
</P>
<P>
So far, half of the 30 weightlifting world records have been
improved upon in the current Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
Of the seven gold medals awarded today, mountain bike racing
which made its debut in the current Olympics drew big crowds into
the Georgia International Horse Park. Holland's Bart Jan Brentjens
won the men's 47.7km event while Italy's Paola Pezzo rode over a
31.8km course of rough terrain in one hour 50 minutes and 51
seconds to claim the gold.
</P>
<P>
Kazakistan's Aleksandr Parygin collected a total of 5,551
points to emerge first in the men's modern pentathlon which
includes 10m pistol shooting, one-touch epee fencing, 300m
freestyle swimming, horse riding and jumping and 4,000m running.
</P>
<P>
A Brazilian pair emerged on top in the Tornado yachting event
while a Chinese duo defeated their compatriots to take the table
tennis men's doubles title.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's last gold medal was won by the United States when its
softball team defeated China 3-0 in the gold-medal final match.
</P>
<P>
Of the 271 golds on offer in the current Games, 170 have been
awarded with the United States and Russia taking 25 and 19
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Another 18 gold medals will be decided Wednesday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
