<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liu Edges Huang Out to Reach Top Four in Olympic Table Tennis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- China's world runner-up Liu
Guoliang nipped Canadian Johnny Huang in four sets to reach the
men's singles semi-finals at the Olympic table tennis tournament
here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The 20-year-old, who combined with world number one Kong
Linghui to take the men's doubles gold medal three hours ago, beat
the Canadian 9-21, 21-19, 21-16, 21-16.
</P>
<P>
Liu, sixth-ranked penholder, didn't get used to Huang's fast
attacks from both sides and lost the first set in less than 10
minutes.
</P>
<P>
But Huang's momentum ended here as Liu put up more aggressive
game to win three sets in a row.
</P>
<P>
"Huang is really difficult to cope with," Liu said. "If I had
lost nerves in the second set, the game would have been over for
me."
</P>
<P>
Huang produced the biggest upset in the tournament as he beat
defending champion Jan-Ove Waldner of Sweden on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Liu is to take on the winner of the match between German Jorg
Rosskopf and South Korean Kim Taek-Soo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
