<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mideast Peace Dominates Mubarak-Clinton Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian president stressed
on Tuesday that the "first and foremost" thing to maintain
momentum for the Middle East peace process is to abide by the
land-for-peace formula, and any activities against it should be
terminated.
</P>
<P>
Hosni Mubarak made the unequivocal statement at a joint news
conference with U.S President Bill Clinton following their White
House consultations, in which the Middle East peace was a
dominating issue, on his third day of visit to the United States.
</P>
<P>
"A just and fair peace must be based on formula, which was
proposed by the co-sponsors of the Madrid peace conference of
October 1991 and accepted by all parties," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Activities which are inconsistent with the requirements and
spirit of peace, such as settlement activities and the
confiscation of lands, should be terminated," he added.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak warned Israel's Likud leader Benjamin Netanyahu, who
replaced moderate Labour leader Shimon Peres after a narrow
victory in the May election, that risks could be involved if the
peace process is terminated or set back.
</P>
<P>
"We are all quite aware of the risks involved if the peace
process is terminated or set back. No party would benefit from
this prospect," said the Egyptian president, who met Netanyahu in
Cairo before leaving for Washington.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak is in Washington to press the United States to continue
what he called "its essential role" in the Middle East peace
process, which the Arab world is uneasy to be reversed with
inertia on the side of the Clinton administration towards
Netanyahu's controversial policies.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, whose talks earlier this month with Netanyahu in
Washington resulted in nothing positive with regard to the peace
process, adviced people to be "a little patient" before he had a
"chance to put Israel back on track".
</P>
<P>
He told the joint press conference that "a slowdown period was
inevitable because of the (Israeli) election".
</P>
<P>
"I know it's frustrating, but we just have to let a little of
that time elapse," he said.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believe that the Clinton administration would
rather keep the situations as it is in the Middle East than to
prod Israel to make any compromises, fearing that it might provoke
Jewish-Americans, who support whatever government elected in
Israel, to turn their back to the U.S. incumbent president in the
upcoming election.
</P>
<P>
In answering the question of world-wide anti-terrorist
activities, proposed by President Clinton, Mubarak made it clear
that only peace can solve the the problem, not vice versa as
Netanyahu emphasized during his visit to Washington when he said
only security could yield peace.
</P>
<P>
"If we could maintain peace, if we could reach a comprehensive
settlement in this critical part of the world... I think we could
put an end to at least 95 percent of the terroristic actions in
the world," he said.
</P>
<P>
There is also disagreement between Clinton and Mubarak in
sanctions against countries which the United States deems as
"terrorist" nations or at least the bases for terrorist groups.
</P>
<P>
"We would like to form a committee... to find out how could we
punish not the whole people of a country but to punish the group
who's responsible about terrorism in any country in the world.
</P>
<P>
"Because if we are going to punish the whole country in any
place because of terrorism, the people will get upset, get
furious... Just punishing the whole people create terrible
problems," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
