<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Serbs Receive Unequal Treatment Ahead of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Serbs in the Republika Srpska and
Serb Refugees are not treated equally with Muslims and Croats
ahead of Bosnia's September elections, Slobodan Kovac, member of
Bosnia's Temporary Electoral Commission, complained today.
</P>
<P>
"Serbs sheltering in third countries have to register with
embassies of the Muslim-Croat federation, while thousands of
Croatian Serbs expelled from the Republic of Serb Krajina who wish
to remain in the Republika Srpska are denied the right to vote,"
Tanjug news agency quoted Kovac, a judge of the Serb
constitutional court, as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE),
which is in charge of Bosnia's elections, has rejected the Serbs'
request that all Serb refugees in third countries be enabled to
register elsewhere and not only in embassies of the Muslim-Croat
federation, he said.
</P>
<P>
Kovac also stressed the issue arising from a request by Bosnian
Croats sheltering in Croatia who hold dual citizenship to be
allowed to vote in municipalities situated near the border with
the Republika Srpska.
</P>
<P>
"No one can prevent them from doing so if they had been
registered as citizens of Bosnia-Herzegovina in the 1991 census,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Bosnia's elections will be held in 61 municipalities, while
lists of candidates will be ratified by August 15. The
registration of voters began on July 22 and will end on August 5.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
