<HEADLINE> Spaniards Win Tornado Sailing Gold Medal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Fernando Leon and Jose Luis
Ballester of Spain didn't even sail Tuesday and still won the gold
medal in the Tornado class Olympic sailing competition in
Savannah, Georgia.
</P>
<P>
With a huge lead after Monday's race, the Spanish team sat out
Tuesday's final race but finished with 30 points, good for a
12-point victory over silver medalists Mitch Booth and Andrew
Landenberger of Australia.
</P>
<P>
Lars Grael and Kiko Pellicano of Brazil won the bronze medal
with 43 points, while teams from Austria and Italy were one point
back despite finishing first and second in Tuesday's race.
</P>
<P>
With four of the 10 classes having completed their regatta on
Monday, there were only five races schedule Tuesday _ the final
for the catamarans and two races each in the men's and women's 470
double-handed dinghy class.
</P>
<P>
Japan's Yumiko Shige and Alicia Kinoshita moved into a share of
the lead in the women's 470 class with the current world
champions, Theresa Zabell and Begona Via Dufresne of Spain. Each
team had 23 points.
</P>
<P>
The runaway leader in the men's division was the Ukraine team
of Yevhen Braslavets and Ihor Matviyenko.
</P>
<P>
Portugal's Vitor Rocha and Nuno Barreto placed second Tuesday
to remain in second place with 40 points, while Great Britain's
Ian Walker and John Merricks were lodged in third with 43 points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
