<P>
ATLANTA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Italian mountain biker Paolo Pezzo
upset world champion Alison Sydor of Canada to seize the gold
medal in the women's mountain bike cross country race at the 26th
Olympic Games here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Pezzo, 27, peddled home in one hour, 50 minutes and 51 seconds
in the 31.8 kilometers race. The women's mountain bike cross
country race is making its Olympic debut.
</P>
<P>
Sydor, who won women's cross country race at World
Championships in 1994 and 1995, finished second in 1:51:58 to take
the silver. Susan MeMattei of the United States, silver medalist
at the 1994 world championships, was third in 1:52:36 for the
bronze.
</P>
<P>
At the Georgia International Horse Park just outside Atlanta,
Sydor led a group of six bikers to pull away from the field in the
first lap, but DeMattei took over the lead at the beginning of the
second in the three-lap race.
</P>
<P>
Pezzo, who crashed shortly after the start and walked her bike
on an upward slope, caught up with the leading group and broke
away from it half way into the second lap, leaving DeMattei and
Sydor chasing closely behind.
</P>
<P>
Pezzo expanded her lead to more than one minute at the
beginning of the third lap and led the rest of the way, cruising
to victory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
