<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Railway Links Sarajevo to Adriatic Coast Re-opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, July 30 (Xinhua) - A vital railway linking the
Bosnian inland with the Adriatic sea was in service again on
Tuesday after more than three years of disruption caused by the
country's ethnic war.
</P>
<P>
To mark the occasion, a train left Sarajevo railway station
this morning for Ploce, an Adriatic port on the Croatian coast,
with 250 passengers aboard including President Alija Izetbegovic,
other senior Bosnian officials and international representatives.
</P>
<P>
"Today Bosnia goes out to the sea and into the wide world,"
Izetbegovic said in an emotional speech before the departure.
</P>
<P>
The 190-kilometer railway from Sarajevo to Ploce via the
southern Bosnian city of Mostar was restored with aid from the
European countries, Saudi Arabia as well as neighboring Croatia.
</P>
<P>
The European Union contributed more than 6.7 million Ecus (8.7
million US dollars) in cash and equipment for repairs to the line,
while Germany helped reconstruct two bridges outside Mostar which
was blown up during fightings between Muslims and Croats.
</P>
<P>
Although Bosnia has a short section of coast at the town of
Neum, it is not viable for maritime transportation for which
Bosnia had to rely on Ploce even before the war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
