<HEADLINE> Prime Suspect Rumored as Security Personnel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- A security personnel was reported
as the prime suspect for the bomb explosion at the Centennial
Olymic Park on Saturday that claimed two fatalities and injuried
112 people.
</P>
<P>
"I've heard of that in the conversation with you and others,"
said A.D. Frazier, chief operating officer of the Atlanta
Committee for the Olympic Games (ACOG) here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"But maybe it is another rumor," Frazier was quick to add.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think this person in question is contracted by us," he
said, adding that among the security personnel at the Park were
those provided by the tenants.
</P>
<P>
For the Olympic Games, the ACOG has accreditated some 6,000
security personnel "through background information checks".
</P>
<P>
"However, the Park is a public place not a competition venue"
which provides open access to the public, said Frazier.
</P>
<P>
In the wee hours of Saturday, a home-made crude pipe bomb with
nails and screws attached, exploded before the arrival of a bomb
disposable squad from the Atlanta Police Office, claiming two
lives including a Turkish TV cameraman who was died of heart
attack.
</P>
<P>
Among the injuried, 97 were Americans and two Britons.
</P>
<P>
Those 16 remained in hospitals but in stable condition "are
expected to be released soon", said Frazier.
</P>
<P>
After the tragedy, the Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI)
dispatched its agents to the spot and concerned authorities sealed
off the Park for three days till Tuesday morning when it was
re-opened to the public with random bag check taken as additional
security measure.
</P>
<P>
Beverly Harvard, Chief of Police in Atlanta, said early that a
911 caller, among a dozen of bomb calls, said "a bomb will explode
in the park in 30 minutes" without specific information on its
location.
</P>
<P>
Woody Johnson, the chief FBI agent, said the caller was "a
white male with indistinguishable accent" who made the call in the
Days Inn hotel, two blocks away from the Park.
</P>
<P>
And they have flown the bomb fragments, the phone to the FBI
headquarters in Washington D.C. for revaluation, Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
So far, neither the law-enforcement forces here nor the FBI was
ready to confirm the report concerning the prime suspect. 
</P>
</TEXT>
