<HEADLINE> Olympic Park Reopens 3-Day After Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Atlanta's Centennial Olympic Park
reopened today, three days after a bomb blast in the park that led
to two people dead and more than 100 injured.
</P>
<P>
A crowd of thousands, many in sombre mood, waited outside
before the opening and then filed quietly in through tightly
controlled checkpoints.
</P>
<P>
The park was closed after the bomb blast on Saturday for
investigation. Police, FBI agents and forensic experts handed the
park back to Olympic organizers after they had completed a search
for clues.
</P>
<P>
Security measures have been redoubled in the park. Police,
soldiers, plain clothes officers and explosives-sniffing dogs
patrolled the area.
</P>
<P>
Atlanta Mayor Bill Campbell and his family were among the first
visitors. He told CNN in the park he had come back for the opening
as "a tangible symbol of my commitment to these Games continuing."
</P>
<P>
"People understand that if you do otherwise in responding to
terrorism, you allow those who have committed these heinous acts
to be victorious and we will never do that," said Campbell.
</P>
<P>
Former Atlanta mayor Andrew Young, who co-chairs the Games
organizing committee, was due to lead a memorial service at the
park later today.
</P>
<P>
Investigation is continuing, but investigators believe a white
American male was the prime suspect. He made a warning call about
the bomb from a nearby public phone shotly before the bomb
blasted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
