<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Fines U.S. Drug Maker for Excessive Pricing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- A federal regulator of Canada has
slapped 2.4 million Canadian dollars in penalties on a U.S. drug
maker for overcharging a patented medicine used to treat children
with respiratory infections.
</P>
<P>
The ruling from the Patented Medicine Prices Review Board
against California-based ICN Pharmaceuticals Inc. marks the first
time in its nine-year history that the board has used its full
powers against a pharmaceutical company, local press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The board ordered ICN to pay immediately 1.2 million Canadian
dollars (one Canadian dollar equal to 0.73 US dollars), an amount
equal to estimated unwarranted profits ICN earned by selling the
drug for excessive price since 1994.
</P>
<P>
Under the ruling, ICN must also drop the price of the drug,
called Virazole, to 200 dollars a vial from the current price of
1,540 dollars in the next three years, which will cost it an
additional 1.2 million dollars in lost revenue.
</P>
<P>
After 1999, ICN must comply with the board's regulated price
for Virazole, which is around 400 dollars a vial.
</P>
<P>
ICN is appealing the ruling, which was made yesterday. It
argued that the board has no jurisdiction over Virazole and that
the patent on the drug has expired, making it exempt from the
patent law.
</P>
<P>
The board contended that while an initial patent has expired,
other patents still prevent rival versions of the drug from coming
on the market.
</P>
<P>
In Canada, drugs that are no longer under patent aren't
regulated by the board because they are subject to competition
from other drug makers.
</P>
<P>
Established in 1987, the board reviews the price of drugs twice
a year in order to ensure that companies don't increase prices
beyond the consumer price index.
</P>
<P>
ICN increased the price of Virazole by 83 percent to 750
dollars a vial in 1994. It raised the price up to 1,540 a vial a
year later, saying the price increases were intended to bring the
Canadian price of Virazole in line with the U.S. price. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
