<HEADLINE> Whitewater Jurors Report Deadlock </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Federal jurors said Tuesday
they were deadlocked in the Whitewater trial of two Arkansas
bankers accused of illegally using their bank funds to promote
Bill Clinton's political career, but the judge sent them back for
more deliberations.
</P>
<P>
"We as a jury have come to the conclusion we are locked, and we
are seeking advice of your honor," the jury in the trial of Herby
Branscum Jr. and Robert M. Hill said in a note to U.S. District
Judge Susan Webber Wright, according to media reports from
Little Rock, Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
The judge then summoned the jury into the courtroom and reread
them an instruction asking them to do everything possible to reach
a conclusion.
</P>
<P>
Before the jury was summoned, defense attorney Dan Guthrie told
the judge: "If they say they are hopelessly deadlocked, we should
declare a mistrial."
</P>
<P>
Deliberations began Thursday afternoon in the six-week trial
and continued all day Friday and a full day on Monday. Today was
their fourth.
</P>
<P>
Branscum and Hill are charged with misapplication of bank funds
and conspiring to use money from their Perry County Bank to pay
for political contributions to Clinton and others.
</P>
<P>
They also are accused of concealing 52,500 dollars in cash
withdrawals by Clinton's 1990 gubernatorial campaign from the
Internal Revenue Service.
</P>
<P>
The government contends the two were motivated to break the law
by a desire for political power. The bankers say they were already
politically connected and had no need to ingratiate themselves
with Clinton or other candidates.
</P>
<P>
They claim money they received from the Perry County Bank
around the time of their political donations reimbursed them for
legitimate business expenses.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
