<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece's Conscription Bill Unveiled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The Greek defense ministry today
unveiled a draft law on conscription aimed at solving the shortage
of military personnel caused by the country's demographic problem.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Gerassimos Arsenis said that the bill would
be tabled in parliament for voting by the Summer session in
September.
</P>
<P>
The bill lowers the age for compulsory military service from
the current 20 years to 19 years, while enabling the national
defense minister to revise the age limit according to requirements.
</P>
<P>
It also provides incentives in the form of reduced service for
young men who do not exercise their right to postpone their
enlistment
</P>
<P>
The ministry's target is to eventually establish a 12-month term
of service plus two or three Summers.
</P>
<P>
Under the bill, Arsenis said, postponements will be granted for
studies, including post-graduate studies, up until the age of 28,
after which no further postponement will be given.
</P>
<P>
According to ministry figures, 40 percent of young Greek men
begin their military service immediately upon reaching the required
age, while 30-35 percent postpone it, in order to study, until
they reach 25 years of age.
</P>
<P>
Under the bill, conscientious objectors will be able to complete
their military service in unarmed roles, although no provision
has been made for alternative service for this category. The issue
of alternative service for conscientious objectors is expected to
be examined within the framework of discussions on the revision
of the constitution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960731.0315 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Smith Urges Reconciliation in Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The Commander of the NATO-led
peace Implementation Force (IFOR) in Bosnia, U.S. Admiral Leighton
Smith, today urged the leaders of the three ethnic groups to work
hard for reconciliation among the local people in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
The outgoing IFOR commander, before flying out of Sarajevo to
end his seven-month mission in Bosnia, said that political leaders
in Bosnia who fail to urge their peoples to reconciliate run the
risk of being responsible for renewed fighting in the country.
</P>
<P>
He also warned that politicians on all three sides in Bosnia --
Serbs, Muslims and Croats -- may use upcoming elections in Bosnia,
scheduled for September 14, for deepening existing divisions,
according to Tanjug news agency.
</P>
<P>
Smith told reporters that there was no peace in Bosnia but an
absence of war.
</P>
<P>
Smith, who was flying for NATO's Southern Command base in
Naples, will be replaced by U.S. Admiral Joseph Lopez.
</P>
<P>
Under Smith's command, IFOR has achieved remarkable progress in
keeping peace in Bosnia and almost fully implemented the military
aspect of the Dayton agreement.
</P>
<P>
Smith also called for the extradition to the Hague criminal
tribunal of Serb leader Radovan Karadzic and his military chief
Ratko Mladic, both have been indicted for war criminals. The
Bosnian Serbs would suffer as long as Karadzic and Mladic were
free, he added.
</P>
<P>
Karadzic resigned as Serb republic president and chairman of
the Serb ruling Serbian Democratic Party on July 19 under strong
international pressure. But Mladic still remains the commander of
the Serb army.
</P>
<P>
"The entire Serb population is basically getting a bad rap
because they are being painted with that black tar brush saying
they are guilty. But they are not," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
