<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Backs Estonia's 1996-97 Economic Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) today approved a 13-month stand-by credit of equivalent 20
million U.S. dollars in support of the Estonian Government's
1996-97 economic program.
</P>
<P>
The economic and financial program for 1996-97, which is
financed by the new stand-by credit, seeks to enhance the economic
recovery while preserving macroeconomic stabilization in the
country. The program is targeted at real GDP growth of 3.1 percent
in 1996 and 4.4 percent in 1997, reducing inflation to 27.1
percent in 1996 and 21 percent in 1997. The program also aims at
containing the external current account at 6.9 percent of GDP this
year and 5.8 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Estonia joined the IMF in May 1992. Its quota is about 68
million dollars and its outstanding use of IMF financing currently
totals about 86 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960731.0317 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Plavsic Rules out Integration with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Bosnian Serb acting President
Biljana Plavsic today excluded the possibility of an integration
association of the Serb entity in Bosnia-Herzegovina with the
Muslim-Croat federation.
</P>
<P>
"An integration would create a latent danger of a new genocide
of the Serb people," Plavsic said during a meeting with
politicians and businessmen from Prijedor, a Serb town in
northwest Bosnia, according to Tanjug news agency report from
Prijedor.
</P>
<P>
The bloody Bosnian civil war started in April 1992 because the
Serbs, who accounted for one-third of the population in Bosnia,
opposed the independent bid of the Muslims and Croat in the
country, fearing possible discrimination as minority after Bosnia
broke away from the former Yugoslavia. The Serbs' final goal is to
separate from Bosnia to merge with neighboring Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Under the Dayton peace agreement signed in December of last
year, Bosnia is preserved to be a single state with two equal
entities -- Republika Srpska and Muslim-Croat federation.
</P>
<P>
Plavsic said that integration aspirations were fomented by
foreign influence in an attempt to weaken the national feelings of
the Serb people in Serb entity Republika Srpska.
</P>
<P>
Any Serb party which treasures national interests cannot uphold
such aspirations, said Plavsic, who assumed full presidential
duties this month when Serb President Radovan Karadzic formerly
resigned two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Speaking about the first post-war elections scheduled in
September in Bosnia, Plavsic said that it was necessary to
strengthen the national front of the Serb people whose victory at
the September elections would mean a final recognition of the
Republika Srpska's statehood. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
